const _INIT_trainingModules=[
    {id:1,name:"Water Heater Install — Gas",category:"Plumbing",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What is the minimum clearance required around a gas water heater for combustion air per Colorado code?",a:"Minimum 12 inches of clearance on all sides. The unit needs adequate combustion air — in confined spaces you must provide two openings, one within 12 inches of the top and one within 12 inches of t..."},
        {q:"What gas pressure should you verify at the inlet of a residential gas water heater before startup?",a:"7 inches of water column (WC) for natural gas. Check with a manometer at the inlet test port. If pressure is below 5\" WC or above 10\" WC, do NOT light the unit — call the gas company. LP gas should read 11\" WC."},
        {q:"When installing a new gas water heater, what must be installed on the cold water inlet and why?",a:"An expansion tank on the cold water inlet. When water heats, it expands. With a check valve or PRV on the main line, there's nowhere for pressure to go. The expansion tank absorbs thermal expansion..."},
        {q:"What is the correct T&P valve discharge pipe requirements?",a:"Must be the same diameter as the T&P valve outlet (3/4\" minimum). Must terminate within 6 inches of the floor or to the exterior. Cannot be threaded on the discharge end. Cannot be reduced in size. No valves or caps on the end. Material must be rated for 210°F — copper or CPVC."},
        {q:"A customer asks 'Can't I just install a 50 gallon to replace my 40 gallon?' What's the JT expert answer?",a:"'Great question — a larger tank means you'll rarely run out of hot water. But we need to check three things first: Will it fit in the space? Is your gas line sized to handle the higher BTU demand? ..."},
        {q:"What is the #1 reason gas water heaters fail prematurely in Northern Colorado?",a:"Sediment buildup from hard water. Greeley/Evans/Windsor water runs 15-25 grains of hardness. Sediment settles on the bottom of the tank, creates a barrier between the flame and the water, causes th..."},
        {q:"When connecting a gas water heater, what sealant is approved for gas line connections?",a:"Yellow Teflon tape (gas rated) OR pipe dope rated for gas (Rector-Seal or equivalent). NEVER use white Teflon tape on gas — it's not rated for gas and can deteriorate. Apply tape clockwise (as you ..."},
        {q:"What's the Good/Better/Best presentation for a standard 50-gallon gas water heater replacement?",a:"Good: Standard 6-year tank, basic installation, existing connections. Better: 9-year tank with powered anode rod, expansion tank, new supply lines, sediment trap, and drain pan. Best: 12-year premi..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the BTU input required for a gas water heater to deliver a 60°F temperature rise at 3.5 GPM continuous flow. Show the formula.",a:"Formula: BTU/hr = GPM × 500 × ΔT. So: 3.5 × 500 × 60 = 105,000 BTU/hr input required. A standard 50-gallon tank has 40,000 BTU input — it can't sustain 3.5 GPM continuously; it relies on stored hot..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A gas water heater is backdrafting — you measure positive pressure in the draft hood. Walk through every possible cause and the systematic diagnostic.",a:"Backdrafting causes (systematic): 1) VENT BLOCKAGE: bird nest, collapsed liner, ice dam (common in CO winter), disconnected vent connector. Inspect entire vent run to termination. 2) INADEQUATE COM... vent for natural draft. 5) IMPROPER VENT PITCH: must slope upward 1/4\" per foot to the chimney. A sag creates a trap. 6) SHARED VENT (chimney) issues: if the furnace is also venting through the same chimney, the combined BTU may exceed chimney capacity. CRITICAL: backdrafting puts CO in the home. If you can't resolve it during the visit, shut down the appliance and red-tag it."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the thermosiphon effect in a water heater system and how it affects piping design on recirculation loops.",a:"Thermosiphon (gravity recirculation): hot water is less dense than cold water, creating natural convection. Hot water rises through the hot supply pipe, cools at distant fixtures, and falls back th..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A 10-year-old water heater has a weeping T&P valve that won't stop even after replacement. The tank is not overheating (thermostat reads 120°F). What's causing it and what's the fix?",a:"If the T&P valve is not responding to temperature (since it's at 120°F, well under the 210°F rating), it must be responding to PRESSURE. The T&P valve opens at 150 PSI. Causes: 1) THERMAL EXPANSION..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What are the differences between a natural draft, power vent, direct vent, and condensing water heater? When do you specify each?",a:"Natural Draft (atmospheric): Uses a draft hood and Type B metal vent. Hot exhaust rises naturally through the chimney. Cheapest, simplest. Requires adequate combustion air in the space. Cannot be i..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's water heater is making a loud rumbling/popping sound. Diagnose the cause and explain the physics behind it.",a:"The rumbling sound is caused by steam bubble formation under a layer of sediment. Physics: In Greeley's hard water (15-25 grains), calcium carbonate precipitates out of the water and settles to the..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Size the gas line for a new 75-gallon, 76,000 BTU water heater that's 30 feet from the gas meter with two 90° elbows. Show your work using the gas pipe sizing table.",a:"Gas pipe sizing uses BTU demand, pipe length, and allowable pressure drop (typically 0.5 inches WC from meter to appliance). Step 1: Calculate equivalent length — each 90° elbow adds approximately ... pipe. So: 30 feet + (2 × 5) = 40 feet equivalent length. Step 2: Reference the gas pipe sizing table (IFGC Table 402.4): At 40 feet equivalent length and 0.5\" WC pressure drop, 3/4\" pipe carries 173,000 BTU for natural gas. 76,000 BTU < 173,000 → 3/4\" pipe is adequate. HOWEVER: if this line ALSO feeds other appliances (furnace at 80,000 BTU, range at 65,000 BTU, dryer at 35,000 BTU), total demand = 256,000 BTU. At 40 feet, you'd need 1\" pipe (capacity ~350,000 BTU). This is why master plumbers size from the METER, not just the individual appliance. The most common code violation on water heater installs is an undersized gas line feeding multiple appliances — the new WH works fine alone but starves when the furnace kicks on."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the purpose of each safety device on a gas water heater and the failure mode of each.",a:"1) THERMOCOUPLE/THERMOPILE: Generates millivoltage (20-30mV) from pilot flame heat. If pilot dies, voltage drops, gas valve closes within 30 seconds. Failure mode: corroded tip loses voltage output..."}
      ]},
    {id:2,name:"Water Heater Install — Electric",category:"Plumbing",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What is the typical circuit requirement for a standard residential electric water heater?",a:"30-amp dedicated circuit with 10/2 NM-B wire for units up to 4,500 watts. A 50-gallon electric typically has two 4,500W elements running at 240V. Breaker must be a 2-pole 30A. If the existing circu..."},
        {q:"How do you test if an electric water heater element is bad?",a:"Turn off the breaker. Disconnect wires from the element. Set multimeter to Ohms/Resistance. Touch probes to the two element terminals. Good element: 10-16 ohms for a 4,500W element. Infinite/OL rea..."},
        {q:"What's the most common mistake apprentices make on electric water heater installs?",a:"Not filling the tank completely before energizing. Turning on the breaker with a dry or partially filled tank will burn out the upper element in under 60 seconds — that's a $250 callback. Fill the ..."},
        {q:"A customer with an electric water heater says they're only getting lukewarm water. Walk through the diagnosis.",a:"1) Check both thermostats — are they set to 120°F? 2) Press the red reset button on the upper thermostat — if it clicks, the high-limit tripped (could indicate failing element). 3) Test both elemen..."},
        {q:"When is it appropriate to recommend a heat pump water heater to a customer?",a:"When the electric water heater is in a space with at least 700 cubic feet of air (roughly 10x10x7 room), temperature stays above 40°F year-round, and the customer cares about energy savings. Heat p..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: An electric water heater trips the breaker every time it fires. The elements test good at 12 ohms. What's the systematic diagnostic?",a:"Elements test good (12 ohms for 4,500W at 240V is correct: R = V²/P = 57,600/4,500 = 12.8Ω). So the problem is elsewhere: 1) TEST ELEMENT TO GROUND: Set multimeter to resistance, one probe on eleme..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the recovery rate and first-hour rating for a 50-gallon electric water heater with two 4,500W elements. How does this compare to gas?",a:"Recovery rate formula: GPH = (BTU input × efficiency) / (8.33 × ΔT). Electric: 4,500W = 15,354 BTU/hr. Efficiency ≈ 98% (nearly all heat enters water). At 90°F rise (60°F inlet to 120°F): GPH = (15..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer with an electric WH wants to go tankless electric. What electrical requirements make this impractical in most existing homes?",a:"A whole-home electric tankless (capable of 3+ GPM at 60°F rise) requires approximately 27-36 kW of power. That's 112-150 amps at 240V — THREE to FOUR 40A double-pole breakers with 8/2 wire EACH. Mo..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the wiring difference between a simultaneous and non-simultaneous (sequential) electric water heater, and why it matters for element replacement.",a:"Non-simultaneous (standard residential): The upper thermostat is a DPDT (double-pole, double-throw) switch. When cold water fills the tank, the upper thermostat energizes the UPPER element first. O..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the anode rod's electrochemical function, and how do you determine which anode type to install in Greeley's water chemistry?",a:"Electrochemistry: The anode rod is a sacrificial electrode made of a more reactive metal than the steel tank. Per the galvanic series, magnesium and aluminum are more anodic (reactive) than steel. ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: An electric water heater trips the upper thermostat high-limit (ECO) repeatedly after reset. The elements test good and thermostats appear to be set correctly. What's happening?",a:"If both elements test good (10-16 ohms) and thermostats are set to 120°F, the problem is likely: 1) GROUNDED ELEMENT — element tests good for resistance but is leaking current to the tank body. Tes..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the recovery rate and first-hour rating for a 50-gallon electric water heater with 4,500W elements at 240V. Explain why this matters for sizing.",a:"Recovery rate formula: Recovery (GPH) = (Wattage × 3.412) / (ΔT × 8.33). At a 90°F rise (cold groundwater at 40°F in Colorado to 130°F setpoint): (4,500 × 3.412) / (90 × 8.33) = 15,354 / 749.7 = 20..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer has a hybrid/heat pump water heater that keeps reverting to electric-only mode in the winter. Why is this happening and what's the solution?",a:"Heat pump water heaters extract heat from surrounding air. In winter, if the unit is in an unheated garage or basement where temperatures drop below 40°F, the heat pump becomes inefficient and the ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain how a simultaneous-operation electric water heater differs from a standard non-simultaneous unit, and when you'd specify one over the other.",a:"Standard (non-simultaneous): Only ONE element heats at a time. Upper thermostat has priority — when the top is cold, it heats first, then hands off to the lower element. This is why a 4,500W/4,500W..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's electric water heater produces water that smells like rotten eggs. The anode rod is intact and the water supply smells fine when cold. What's the chemistry behind this and the fix?",a:"The rotten egg smell (hydrogen sulfide gas) is caused by sulfate-reducing bacteria reacting with the MAGNESIUM ANODE ROD. Chemistry: Greeley water contains dissolved sulfates. The magnesium anode r..."}
      ]},
    {id:3,name:"Tankless Water Heater Install",category:"Plumbing",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the three most critical requirements for a tankless water heater installation?",a:"1) Gas line sizing — tankless units require 3/4\" minimum gas line, often 1\" for units over 180,000 BTU. The existing 1/2\" line from the old tank WILL NOT work. 2) Venting — Category III stainless steel or PVC concentric venting. Cannot use existing B-vent from the old tank. 3) Condensate drain — condensing units produce acidic condensate that must drain to a floor drain, condensate pump, or exterior. All three add cost the customer doesn't expect — present it upfront."},
        {q:"A customer says 'My neighbor has a tankless and loves it.' What questions do you ask before recommending one?",a:"'That's great — let me make sure it's the right fit for your home.' 1) How many bathrooms? (Sizes the unit) 2) Do you have a recirculation demand? (Eliminates cold water sandwich) 3) Where's your c..."},
        {q:"What is the 'cold water sandwich' effect and how do you solve it?",a:"When a tankless unit shuts off between uses, hot water sits in the pipes. Next use, you get: hot (residual) → cold (fresh water before burner fires) → hot (burner engaged). The customer feels an un..."},
        {q:"How often should a tankless water heater be descaled in the Greeley area, and what does the service include?",a:"Every 6-12 months due to our extremely hard water (15-25 grains). Service includes: isolate the unit with service valves, connect a pump with food-grade white vinegar, circulate for 45-60 minutes, ..."},
        {q:"What's the typical BTU requirement calculation for sizing a tankless unit?",a:"Formula: Flow Rate (GPM) × Temperature Rise × 500 = BTU needed. In Colorado, incoming water is ~45°F in winter. Target output 120°F. Rise = 75°F. For 2 showers running (2.5 GPM each = 5 GPM): 5 × 7..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A tankless unit displays error code E003 (ignition failure) intermittently. It works sometimes and fails at other times. Systematic diagnosis?",a:"Intermittent ignition failure is the hardest tankless diagnostic. Systematic approach: 1) GAS PRESSURE: check both static and dynamic pressure at the unit. Static should be 7\" WC (NG), dynamic (while firing) should not drop below 5\" WC. If dynamic drops low, the gas line is undersized or another appliance is stealing capacity. Test with the furnace running simultaneously — this is when the problem shows. 2) VENTING: check for partial blockage — a bird starting a nest, condensate pooling in a low spot. Intermittent = partial obstruction that sometimes affects combustion air. 3) FLAME ROD: the flame sensing rod builds carbon over time. Even a thin layer causes intermittent detection failure. Clean with fine emery cloth — do NOT use sandpaper. 4) IGNITER: check igniter spark gap. If the ceramic is cracked, spark is inconsistent. 5) GAS VALVE: solenoid may be sticking intermittently — listen for the click when the unit attempts ignition. If no click, the valve is failing. 6) CONDENSATE TRAP: if clogged, back pressure intermittently prevents ignition. Always check the condensate drain first — it's the most overlooked cause of intermittent tankless failures."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between condensing and non-condensing tankless units. What are the installation implications of each?",a:"Non-condensing (82-85% efficient): Extracts primary heat from combustion. Exhaust temperature is 300-400°F. Requires Category III stainless steel venting (NOT PVC — it would melt). Vent material co..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer has a Navien tankless and reports the water gets TOO hot (140°F+) despite the thermostat being set to 120°F. What causes this?",a:"Overheating in tankless is a serious safety issue. Causes: 1) FLOW RATE TOO LOW: Tankless units have a minimum flow rate (typically 0.5-0.75 GPM). If flow drops below minimum while the burner is st..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the payback period for converting from a 50-gallon gas tank ($2,800 installed) to a tankless ($4,800 installed) in a 4-person Greeley household.",a:"Cost difference: $4,800 - $2,800 = $2,000 premium for tankless. Annual gas savings: A 50-gal tank runs 40,000 BTU × ~8 hours/day standby + demand = approximately $45-55/month in gas. A condensing t..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A tankless water heater produces fluctuating temperatures — the customer describes it as a 'cold water sandwich.' Explain the phenomenon and solutions.",a:"Cold water sandwich occurs during interrupted flow. Sequence: 1) First user showers — unit heats water, pipes and heat exchanger are hot. 2) First user finishes — unit shuts off. Hot water remains ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the maximum hot water output for a 199,000 BTU tankless unit with 40°F groundwater and a desired output of 120°F. How many fixtures can it serve simultaneously?",a:"Formula: GPM = BTU / (ΔT × 500). ΔT = 120°F - 40°F = 80°F rise. GPM = 199,000 / (80 × 500) = 199,000 / 40,000 = 4.975 GPM. In Colorado winter, groundwater drops to 37-42°F. At 40°F: ~5.0 GPM. At 37..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A tankless unit displays error code 'LC' (lime/calcium). What does this mean, how do you flush it, and how do you prevent it?",a:"LC code means the unit detected reduced flow through the heat exchanger due to calcium/lime scale buildup. In Greeley's 15-25 grain hard water, this happens every 12-18 months without treatment. Fl..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the venting requirements for a non-condensing vs. condensing tankless water heater and the critical installation differences.",a:"Non-condensing (80-85% efficiency): Exhaust temperature is 300-400°F. Requires CATEGORY III stainless steel vent pipe (not PVC, not B-vent). Stainless steel is expensive — $40-60/foot. Can be direc... PVC to a floor drain, exterior, or condensate pump. 2) Condensate is acidic — if draining into a concrete floor drain, install a condensate neutralizer kit (crushed limestone). 3) Condensing venting can run much longer (100+ equivalent feet in PVC). 4) Cost comparison: stainless vent for non-condensing on a 15-foot run = $600-900 in materials alone. PVC for condensing = $60-80. The condensing unit costs $300-500 more but saves $500+ on venting. Always do the TOTAL INSTALLED COST comparison for the customer."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer has a tankless water heater and a traditional tank water heater in the same home (the previous plumber ran them in series). The customer asks you to evaluate the setup. What do you look for?",a:"Series configuration (tank feeds tankless, or tankless feeds tank) is sometimes done as a pre-heat or buffer strategy but is often problematic. Evaluate: 1) FLOW DIRECTION: If tank preheats water f..."}
      ]},
    {id:4,name:"Sewer Camera Operation",category:"Drain/Sewer",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the three main things you're looking for during a sewer camera inspection?",a:"1) Root intrusion — hair-like roots entering through joints, cracks, or separations. 2) Belly/sag — low spot where water pools and debris collects, eventually causing repeated backups. 3) Pipe cond..."},
        {q:"How do you explain camera findings to a customer who can't understand what they're seeing?",a:"Use the 'arteries' analogy: 'Think of your sewer line like an artery. When it's healthy, everything flows smoothly. What I'm seeing here at 35 feet is like a blockage in an artery — these roots are..."},
        {q:"At what footage mark should you start noting issues and what format should documentation follow?",a:"Start recording from the cleanout and note every finding by footage. Format: [Footage] — [Issue] — [Severity 1-5]. Example: '15ft — Minor joint offset, 2/5. 32ft — Root intrusion moderate, 3/5. 47f..."},
        {q:"What's the difference between presenting a camera inspection as a diagnostic vs. as an add-on sale?",a:"WRONG: 'Do you want to add a camera inspection for $425?' RIGHT: 'I cleared your line and it's flowing now, but I hit resistance at about 35 feet. Without seeing what's in there, I can't tell you i..."},
        {q:"When do you recommend CIPP lining vs. traditional excavation?",a:"CIPP lining when: pipe is 4\"+ diameter, offset is less than 25% of pipe diameter, no complete collapse, and access points exist at both ends. 20-30% less cost, 1 day vs 3-5 days, no landscape destruction, 50-year warranty. Traditional dig when: pipe is completely collapsed, severe belly that needs regrading, pipe is under a structure/foundation, or multiple connections need to be repositioned. Present BOTH options to the customer with pros/cons — let them choose. Lining is typically our Best option."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're pushing the camera and it won't pass a point at 42 feet. You can see water flowing past the camera. What are the possible obstructions and how do you determine which one without excavating?",a:"Water flowing past means the pipe isn't fully collapsed — there's a channel. Possible obstructions: 1) OFFSET JOINT: Pipe sections have shifted vertically or laterally. Camera shows a 'shelf' or 'l... to 3\" at a connection point. Adapter or reducer that the camera can't pass. Solution without excavating: flow test + locating. Mark the camera's position with the sonde locator, note the depth, and compare to the homeowner's knowledge of the property (sewer maps, known utilities). If the obstruction is under concrete/driveway, this changes the repair approach and cost significantly — communicate this upfront."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: How does the sonde/locator work on a camera system, and what factors can give you a false depth reading?",a:"The sonde is a small radio transmitter built into the camera head. It emits a signal at a specific frequency (typically 512 Hz or 33 kHz). The handheld locator on the surface detects this signal. W..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You camera a sewer line and identify Orangeburg pipe. Explain what it is, why it's a problem, and how to present the replacement to the homeowner.",a:"Orangeburg (bituminous fiber pipe): Manufactured from 1945-1972, made from layers of wood pulp/cellulose fiber impregnated with coal tar pitch. Common in post-WWII homes in Greeley built 1950-1970...."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A real estate agent calls and wants a 'quick camera inspection' for a home sale. What's the proper scope and how do you protect JT Plumbing from liability?",a:"Real estate camera inspections are high-liability work. Protocol: 1) SCOPE AGREEMENT: Get it in writing — what are we inspecting? Main sewer line only? All drains? What access points exist? We insp..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Compare cast iron, clay (vitrified), PVC, and ABS sewer pipe. What failure modes and remaining lifespan should you assess for each during camera inspection?",a:"CAST IRON (1920s-1980s): Thick-walled, durable, but corrodes from inside out in acidic drain water. Camera signs: tuberculation (rust nodules reducing diameter), pitting, channeling (bottom erodes ..."}
      ]},
    {id:5,name:"Hydro Jetting Safety & Operation",category:"Drain/Sewer",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What PSI range is used for residential hydro jetting and why should you never exceed it?",a:"1,500-4,000 PSI for residential lines (4\" and 6\" pipe). Never exceed 4,000 PSI on residential — older clay, cast iron, or orangeburg pipes can rupture. ALWAYS camera BEFORE jetting to verify pipe condition. If the pipe is deteriorated, fractured, or has a belly, jetting can make it worse and you own the damage. Commercial lines can go up to 8,000 PSI on larger diameter pipes in good condition."},
        {q:"What PPE is required before operating the hydro jetter?",a:"Full face shield (not just safety glasses — sewage splash is real), heavy rubber gloves (not latex), steel-toe boots, waterproof coveralls or apron, hearing protection (the pump is 85+ dB). If work..."},
        {q:"A customer asks 'Why can't you just use a snake instead of that expensive jetter?' How do you respond?",a:"'Great question — a snake punches a hole through the clog like pushing a stick through a pile of leaves. It gets flow going, but the debris is still on the pipe walls and will build right back up. ..."},
        {q:"What nozzle types should be on every hydro jetting truck and when do you use each?",a:"1) Penetrating nozzle — forward-firing jets for breaking through tough clogs (grease, roots). Use first to open the line. 2) Flushing nozzle — rear-firing jets at 15-30° angle for cleaning pipe wal..."},
        {q:"What should you ALWAYS do before AND after hydro jetting?",a:"BEFORE: 1) Camera inspection to verify pipe condition — this is non-negotiable. 2) Verify cleanout access and downstream flow path. 3) Full PPE on. 4) Notify customer water may be temporarily affec..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're jetting a 4-inch clay sewer line at 3,500 PSI and suddenly the pressure gauge drops to near zero and the pump sounds different. What happened and what do you do?",a:"Sudden pressure loss with pump change = one of two scenarios: 1) PIPE BREACH: The jetting hose broke through a deteriorated section of pipe and is now spraying into the surrounding soil. The nozzle..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What's the difference between jetting nozzle forward thrust, backward thrust, and rotation? How do you calculate the GPM and PSI needed for a specific pipe diameter?",a:"NOZZLE PHYSICS: Rear-facing jets create forward PULL (thrust) — the water shooting backward pushes the nozzle forward into the pipe while simultaneously cleaning the walls. Forward-facing jets crea... orifice each, total flow area = 8 × π × (1/32)² = 0.0245 sq inches. At 3,000 PSI, this flows approximately 5.2 GPM. If your pump only delivers 4 GPM, pressure drops and cleaning is ineffective. ALWAYS match the nozzle orifice configuration to your pump's GPM/PSI curve. Undersized nozzle orifices = cavitation and pump damage. Oversized orifices = insufficient pressure."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A restaurant owner wants jetting service but their grease trap hasn't been pumped in 6 months. What's the protocol and what liability concerns exist?",a:"A full grease trap changes EVERYTHING about the jetting job: 1) DO NOT JET WITHOUT PUMPING THE TRAP FIRST. Jetting a line downstream of a full trap is pointless — the trap will immediately re-conta..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the proper technique for navigating jetting hose around turns and through clean-outs? What mistakes cause equipment damage?",a:"TECHNIQUE: 1) Feed the hose slowly at turns — the nozzle's rear jets will pull it around bends naturally. Don't force it. If the hose won't navigate a turn, the nozzle may be too large or the turn ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: How do you properly decontaminate jetting equipment after a sewage-contact job, and what are the OSHA requirements for bloodborne pathogen exposure?",a:"DECONTAMINATION PROTOCOL: 1) Flush the entire hose and nozzle with clean water for a minimum of 5 minutes. 2) Run a bleach solution (1:10 dilution) through the pump for 2 minutes, then flush with c..."}
      ]},
    {id:6,name:"Sewer Liner Installation",category:"Drain/Sewer",required:false,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"Walk through the CIPP (Cured-In-Place Pipe) lining process step by step.",a:"1) Camera inspection to map all issues and measure pipe diameter/length. 2) Hydro-jet the line completely clean. 3) Measure and cut the liner to length + 12\" extra each end. 4) Saturate liner with two-part epoxy resin using a roller system — full saturation is critical. 5) Invert the liner into the pipe using air pressure or water. 6) Inflate the calibration tube to press liner against pipe walls. 7) Cure with ambient heat (12-24 hours) or UV/steam for faster cure (2-4 hours). 8) Cut ends and reinstate laterals with a robotic cutter. 9) Final camera inspection to verify full adhesion and no wrinkles."},
        {q:"What are the three most common liner installation failures and how do you prevent them?",a:"1) Incomplete resin saturation — dry spots create weak points that can collapse. Prevention: follow manufacturer's resin calculator exactly, use calibrated mixing equipment, visually inspect liner ... extra each end, verify footage measurements with camera twice before cutting."},
        {q:"What's the warranty structure for JT Plumbing liner installations and how should you present it?",a:"JT Plumbing offers: 10-year warranty on installation workmanship. Liner manufacturer provides: 50-year structural warranty. Present it as: 'This liner essentially gives you a brand new pipe inside ..."},
        {q:"What pipe conditions are NOT suitable for CIPP lining?",a:"1) Complete pipe collapse — the liner needs an existing pipe to press against. If the pipe has fully collapsed with no channel, excavation is the only option. 2) Bellies/sags greater than 20% of pi... to 6\" mid-run requires specialized transition liners. 5) Root infiltration with pipe deformation — if roots have crushed the pipe out of round, the liner won't seat properly. 6) Orangeburg pipe (bituminous fiber) — too deteriorated to hold a liner. Always camera inspect AFTER jetting to see the true pipe condition before quoting liner."},
        {q:"How do you present liner vs. traditional excavation to a homeowner? What's the cost comparison?",a:"Script: 'You have two options to fix this sewer line. Option A is traditional excavation — we dig a trench across your yard, remove the old pipe, and install new PVC. This takes 3-5 days, requires ..."},
        {q:"What resin mixing ratio and pot life should you be aware of during lining?",a:"Typical two-part epoxy resin uses a 3:1 or 4:1 base-to-hardener ratio by weight — ALWAYS follow manufacturer specs exactly. Pot life (working time before it starts curing) varies by temperature: at..."},
        {q:"After installation, what does the post-cure camera inspection need to verify?",a:"The final camera inspection is your quality proof. Verify: 1) Full adhesion — no bubbles, delamination, or gaps between liner and host pipe. 2) No wrinkles or folds — the liner should be smooth and..."},
        {q:"A customer asks: 'Won't the liner reduce my pipe size and cause drainage problems?'",a:"'Great question — and it's a common concern. The liner is about 1/4 inch thick, so on a 4-inch pipe, the inside diameter goes from 4 inches to about 3.5 inches. But here's what most people don't re..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the resin quantity needed for lining a 60-foot section of 4-inch sewer pipe. What variables affect this calculation?",a:"Base calculation: Resin volume = π × pipe diameter × liner thickness × pipe length. For a 4\" pipe with 6mm (0.24\") liner: Annular space = π × 4\" × 0.24\" × 720\" (60 feet) = approximately 2,170 cubic inches = 9.4 gallons. But you must account for: 1) RESIN ABSORPTION: Felt liners absorb 2-3x their volume in resin. Add 25-35% for full saturation. 2) PIPE IRREGULARITIES: Cracks, gaps, and rough surfaces absorb extra resin. Add 10-15% for aged pipes. 3) WASTE: Mixing, roller saturation, and end cuts waste 5-10%. TOTAL: 9.4 gallons × 1.5 (absorption + waste factor) = ~14 gallons of mixed resin. At a 3:1 ratio: 10.5 gallons resin + 3.5 gallons hardener. Variables: pipe diameter (larger = exponentially more resin), liner thickness (structural vs. non-structural), pipe condition (rough surfaces absorb more), temperature (hot weather thins resin, requiring slightly more). ALWAYS calculate per manufacturer specs and round UP. Running out of resin mid-installation is a catastrophic failure — the partially saturated liner cures with dry spots and the entire job must be redone."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between CIPP inversion lining and pull-in-place lining. When do you use each method?",a:"INVERSION: The liner is turned inside-out using air or water pressure as it enters the pipe. The resin-saturated side starts on the outside and ends pressed against the pipe wall. Advantages: 1) Sm..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: The ambient temperature during a liner installation is 38°F. How does this affect the cure process, and what modifications are required?",a:"Cold weather dramatically affects CIPP installation: 1) RESIN VISCOSITY: Below 50°F, epoxy resin thickens significantly, making roller saturation harder and potentially creating dry spots. Solution..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer had a liner installed 2 years ago by another company and is experiencing backups again. What are the possible failure modes and how do you assess them?",a:"Camera inspection is mandatory. Possible failures: 1) LINER DELAMINATION: The liner has separated from the host pipe wall, creating a gap where debris catches and roots re-enter. Caused by: incompl..."}
      ]},
    {id:7,name:"Furnace Diagnostics",category:"HVAC",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"A furnace has a flashing LED on the control board showing 3 flashes. What does this typically indicate?",a:"3 flashes typically indicates a pressure switch error — the switch didn't close or opened during operation. Diagnostic steps: 1) Check the inducer motor — is it running? Listen for humming or click..."},
        {q:"What are the five things you check on EVERY furnace call before diagnosing?",a:"1) Thermostat — is it set to HEAT, fan on AUTO, temperature set above room temp? (Sounds basic — fixes 15% of calls.) 2) Filter — a plugged filter is the #1 cause of limit switch trips and reduced ..."},
        {q:"How do you check a heat exchanger for cracks and when is it a safety/replacement call?",a:"Visual inspection: remove the burners and look into each cell with a flashlight and mirror. Look for rust flakes, discoloration, or visible cracks. Combustion analysis: test CO levels in the supply..."},
        {q:"A customer's furnace is cycling on and off every 2-3 minutes. What are the top three causes?",a:"1) Dirty filter restricting airflow → furnace overheats → high-limit switch opens → furnace shuts down → cools off → restarts → repeats. Fix: replace filter, check all returns are open. 2) Flame se..."},
        {q:"How do you present a furnace repair vs. replace decision to a homeowner?",a:"Use the '5,000 rule': multiply the age of the furnace by the cost of repair. If the number exceeds $5,000, replace. Example: 12-year-old furnace, $450 repair = $5,400 → recommend replace. 8-year-ol..."},
        {q:"What's the Lennox furnace model lineup we install and what differentiates each tier?",a:"Good: Lennox ML196E — 96% AFUE, single-stage, standard blower. Reliable workhorse. Better: Lennox EL196E — 96% AFUE, two-stage gas valve, variable-speed blower. Quieter, better humidity control, 30..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the complete ignition sequence on a modern gas furnace, step by step, and identify what component failure corresponds to each step where the sequence can abort.",a:"1) Thermostat calls for heat → control board receives 24V signal. FAIL: bad thermostat, broken R-wire, blown 3A fuse on board. 2) Board energizes inducer motor → creates negative pressure in heat e..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You measure 0.3 microamps on the flame sensor. The furnace locks out after 4 seconds. What's the target reading, why is it low, and how do you restore it?",a:"Target flame sensor reading: 2.0-6.0 microamps DC (varies by manufacturer — Lennox typically wants 2.5+, Carrier wants 3.0+). At 0.3 µA, the board can't confirm a stable flame, so it closes the gas... WC manifold for natural gas. 4) INCORRECT GROUND — the flame sensor circuit uses the burner ground path. If the furnace frame isn't properly grounded (rusted connection, missing bonding wire), the return path is compromised. Clean all ground connections. 5) WRONG SENSOR — some universal sensors have different tip geometries that don't sit properly in the flame. Always use OEM or exact-match replacement. Pro tip: measure with your meter in DC microamp mode — set leads in the µA jack, not the standard mA jack."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A condensing furnace is draining excessive condensate and the PVC vent shows white residue at joints. Diagnose and explain what's happening chemically.",a:"Chemistry: A condensing furnace operates below the dew point of combustion gases (~130°F for natural gas). When flue gas cools below this point, water vapor condenses — this is normal and intention..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain how to perform a combustion analysis on a furnace and what each reading tells you. What are the target values?",a:"Equipment: digital combustion analyzer inserted into the flue pipe (downstream of the heat exchanger, upstream of any dilution air). Readings: 1) CO (Carbon Monoxide): Target <100 PPM air-free for ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A two-stage furnace runs only on high stage and never drops to low. The thermostat is set correctly. What are the possible causes?",a:"Two-stage operation: On a call for heat, the furnace should start on LOW fire (60-65% capacity) and only ramp to HIGH if the thermostat isn't satisfied within a set time (typically 10-12 minutes). ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the Manual J load calculation, why does it matter, and how does oversizing a furnace hurt the customer?",a:"Manual J (ACCA): The industry-standard method for calculating heating and cooling loads for a specific home. It factors in: square footage, insulation values (R-rating of walls, attic, windows), ai..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A high-efficiency furnace (90%+) shows error code for 'limit circuit open' but the filter is clean and all returns are open. What are the less obvious causes?",a:"Beyond the basics (dirty filter, blocked returns), advanced causes: 1) DIRTY SECONDARY HEAT EXCHANGER — in condensing furnaces, the secondary (condensing) heat exchanger collects soot and acidic co... WC on most furnaces indicates duct restriction. 3) DIRTY BLOWER WHEEL — even with a clean filter, fine dust coats the wheel over years. A heavily coated wheel loses 20-40% of its air-moving capacity. Remove, soak, and scrub. 4) WEAK BLOWER CAPACITOR — the motor runs but at reduced RPM. Test the capacitor — if it's lost more than 10% of rated MFD, airflow is reduced. 5) OVERSIZED FURNACE — the BTU output is too high for the duct system. The system heats the air faster than the ducts can move it. Common when a contractor installed the biggest furnace that would fit instead of doing a Manual J load calculation. 6) PLUGGED CONDENSATE DRAIN — backed-up condensate can trigger a secondary limit switch on condensing furnaces. Check and clear the condensate trap and drain line."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between single-stage, two-stage, and modulating furnaces. What specific diagnostic differences exist between them?",a:"Single-stage: Gas valve is either 100% on or off. One speed. Thermostat calls → burner fires at full BTU → reaches setpoint → shuts off. Simple to diagnose — it either works or it doesn't. Temperat... WC manifold, High fire: ~3.5\" WC. 3) If the system always runs on high fire, the staging control or thermostat is faulty. Modulating: Gas valve adjusts from ~40% to 100% in small increments. Variable-speed blower matches airflow to BTU output. Communicating control board talks to the thermostat in real-time. Diagnostics: 1) Requires manufacturer-specific diagnostic tools or app (Lennox iComfort, Trane Nexia). 2) Error codes are more granular — reading the serial communication between components. 3) Flame sensor issues present differently — the flame signal (microamp reading) must be consistent across the modulation range. 4) Gas pressure must be checked at multiple firing rates, not just full fire. Modulating systems are the highest-margin install AND the most complex diagnostic — master-level techs only."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You measure 2.1 microamps on a flame sensor when the manufacturer spec says minimum 1.5 µA. The furnace is operating. Should you be concerned?",a:"YES. While 2.1 µA is above the 1.5 µA minimum lockout threshold, it's dangerously close. A healthy flame sensor should read 4-6 µA. At 2.1 µA, any slight degradation — a cold day where flame charac... WC manifold for natural gas), is the flame engulfing the sensor properly? 3) Check the grounding — a poor furnace ground reduces flame signal. Verify less than 0.5 ohms from the furnace frame to the electrical panel ground. 4) If the sensor is physically corroded or pitted, replace it ($15 part, $0 excuse for a callback). Always record µA readings in your service notes — trending allows you to predict failures before they strand a customer."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's furnace inducer motor runs but the pressure switch won't close. You've checked the hose, condensate drain, and flue — all clear. What advanced diagnostics do you perform?",a:"With the obvious causes eliminated, go deeper: 1) MEASURE ACTUAL PRESSURE — connect a manometer to the pressure switch hose port. Compare the reading to the switch rating (usually -0.40\" to -1.0\" WC). If the inducer is generating adequate negative pressure and the switch still won't close, the switch itself is faulty. 2) TEST THE SWITCH directly — disconnect the hose, apply suction with your mouth (sip straw method) or a hand pump. Listen for the click. If it doesn't click with adequate suction, the switch diaphragm is stuck or the contacts are welded open. Replace it. 3) INDUCER MOTOR WEAK — the motor runs but at reduced RPM (bearing wear, failing capacitor, voltage drop). Measure the actual vacuum generated vs. the switch requirement. A motor that creates -0.30\" WC when the switch needs -0.40\" will never close it. 4) CRACKED INDUCER HOUSING — a hairline crack in the inducer housing leaks air, preventing adequate vacuum. Inspect carefully with a flashlight. 5) BLOCKED CONDENSATE TRAP IN THE INDUCER — some condensing furnaces have a secondary trap inside the inducer assembly that isn't visible without partial disassembly. 6) WRONG REPLACEMENT SWITCH — if someone previously replaced the pressure switch with the wrong specification (tighter tolerance), the inducer may not generate enough vacuum. Verify part number against manufacturer specs."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the complete combustion analysis procedure for a gas furnace. What readings are acceptable and what indicates a problem?",a:"Equipment: Digital combustion analyzer (Testo, Bacharach, or equivalent). Procedure: 1) Let the furnace run for 10 minutes to reach steady-state. 2) Insert the probe into the flue pipe (drill a sma..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer reports their furnace 'short cycles' — it runs for 5 minutes, shuts off for 3 minutes, then restarts. The house never reaches setpoint. What's the systematic diagnostic for a furnace that's too big?",a:"This is classic oversized furnace behavior. Diagnostic confirmation: 1) Calculate the home's heating load using Manual J (room-by-room heat loss calculation). In Northern Colorado, a well-insulated..."}
      ]},
    {id:8,name:"AC Diagnostics & Refrigerant",category:"HVAC",required:true,techs:{1:false,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the correct superheat and subcooling readings for a properly charged R-410A system?",a:"Superheat: 10-15°F at the evaporator outlet (for TXV systems; fixed orifice uses manufacturer target superheat chart). Subcooling: 10-12°F at the condenser outlet. If superheat is high and subcooli..."},
        {q:"R-410A is being phased down. What do you tell a customer who asks about it?",a:"'R-410A is still available and legal to service for the foreseeable future — there's no need to panic. New equipment manufactured after January 2025 will transition to R-454B, which has a lower glo..."},
        {q:"Walk through a systematic AC diagnostic when the customer says 'it's blowing but not cold.'",a:"1) Check thermostat — set to COOL, fan AUTO, setpoint below room temp. 2) Check filter — restricted airflow = frozen coil. 3) Go to the outdoor unit — is the condenser fan running? Is the compresso..."},
        {q:"A capacitor reads 38 MFD but it's rated for 45 MFD. Do you replace it?",a:"YES — a capacitor that's lost more than 10% of its rated capacitance is failing. 38/45 = 84.4%, meaning it's lost 15.6%. The compressor is working harder to start and run, drawing more amps, runnin..."},
        {q:"What's the maximum legal refrigerant leak rate before you must stop adding refrigerant and require repair?",a:"EPA Section 608 requires repair when leak rates exceed: 30% per year for commercial refrigeration, 20% per year for comfort cooling and commercial AC. For residential, there's no specific threshold..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You connect gauges to an R-410A system and read 118 PSI suction / 340 PSI high side with 85°F ambient. Diagnose the system condition using the pressure-temperature relationship.",a:"R-410A saturation temperature at 118 PSI = approximately 40°F (evaporator). At 340 PSI = approximately 100°F (condenser). Analysis: 1) EVAPORATOR: 40°F saturation is normal for cooling (target 35-4..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between a TXV system and a fixed-orifice (piston) system. How does this change your charging method?",a:"TXV (Thermostatic Expansion Valve): Meters refrigerant flow based on suction line superheat. The sensing bulb on the suction line adjusts valve opening to maintain 8-14°F superheat regardless of lo..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: An AC compressor hums loudly and draws locked-rotor amps (LRA) but won't start. The capacitor tests good. Systematic diagnosis?",a:"The compressor is attempting to start but is mechanically or electrically locked. Diagnosis: 1) CHECK START COMPONENTS: Even if the run capacitor is good, the system may need a hard-start kit (pote..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the sensible cooling capacity of a system with 400 CFM per ton, 2.5-ton unit, supply air at 55°F, and return air at 75°F. Is this system performing correctly?",a:"Sensible capacity formula: Q = 1.08 × CFM × ΔT. CFM = 400 × 2.5 tons = 1,000 CFM. ΔT = 75°F - 55°F = 20°F. Q = 1.08 × 1,000 × 20 = 21,600 BTU/hr sensible. A 2.5-ton system = 30,000 BTU/hr total cap..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's AC runs but the house humidity is 65% even though the temperature reaches setpoint. What's the cause and fix?",a:"High humidity with satisfied temperature = the system is removing sensible heat but not enough latent heat (moisture). Causes: 1) OVERSIZED SYSTEM: The most common cause. An oversized AC cools the ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A residential AC system has the correct charge, clean filter, clean coils, and good airflow — but the suction line isn't sweating and the delta-T is only 12°F instead of 18-22°F. What's the diagnosis?",a:"With the basics eliminated, investigate: 1) METERING DEVICE FAILURE — if the TXV (thermostatic expansion valve) is stuck open, refrigerant floods the evaporator coil without proper pressure drop. S..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain how to perform a compressor pump-down test and interpret the results.",a:"Purpose: Determines if the compressor's internal valves are sealing properly (mechanical integrity). Procedure: 1) Connect gauges. Record starting pressures. 2) Close (front-seat) the liquid line s..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What's the correct procedure for recovering, evacuating, and recharging an R-410A system after a compressor replacement?",a:"RECOVERY: 1) Connect recovery machine to the suction service valve. 2) Recover ALL refrigerant into a DOT-approved recovery cylinder (gray with yellow top for R-410A). 3) Weigh the refrigerant reco..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A heat pump system heats well but won't switch to cooling mode. The reversing valve solenoid has 24V but the valve doesn't shift. What's the failure and what are the options?",a:"The reversing valve (4-way valve) physically shifts between heating and cooling mode. If the solenoid energizes (verified 24V) but the valve doesn't shift: 1) STUCK VALVE — the most common failure...."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the purpose and operation of a TXV (Thermostatic Expansion Valve) vs. a fixed orifice metering device. How does this change your diagnostic approach?",a:"FIXED ORIFICE (piston or capillary tube): A precision-drilled hole that restricts refrigerant flow at a fixed rate. Flow varies only with pressure differential across it. Charging method: SUPERHEAT..."}
      ]},
    {id:9,name:"Mini-Split Installation",category:"HVAC",required:false,techs:{1:false,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the key differences in installing a mini-split vs. a traditional split system?",a:"1) Line sets are pre-charged in most mini-splits — you just connect and purge with system refrigerant (no vacuum pump on short runs, though best practice is still pulling a vacuum). 2) Electrical i... from ceiling for airflow. 4) Condensate must drain by gravity or pump — no condensate trap like traditional. 5) Communication wire between indoor/outdoor (3 or 4 conductor, 14-18 AWG). 6) Line set penetration through wall requires slope toward outside for condensate drainage. Biggest mistake: not pulling a vacuum on longer line sets — moisture in the system kills the compressor."},
        {q:"When should you recommend a mini-split over traditional ducted HVAC?",a:"1) Room additions or converted garages with no existing ductwork. 2) Home offices or bonus rooms that are always too hot/cold. 3) Older homes with no space for ductwork. 4) Customer wants zone cont..."},
        {q:"What size mini-split (BTU) is appropriate for a given room? Walk through the sizing process.",a:"Rule of thumb: 20 BTU per square foot as a starting point. A 12×15 room (180 sq ft) needs roughly a 9,000 BTU unit. But you MUST factor in: 1) Ceiling height — rooms over 8ft need 10-15% more. 2) S..."},
        {q:"Describe the correct line set flaring technique and why it's critical.",a:"Mini-split connections use flare fittings, not solder. A bad flare is the #1 cause of refrigerant leaks. Process: 1) Cut tubing square with a tubing cutter — never a hacksaw. 2) Deburr inside AND o... and 58 ft-lbs for 3/8\"."},
        {q:"After connecting everything, what is the correct startup and commissioning procedure?",a:"1) Pull a vacuum on the line set to 500 microns minimum using a vacuum pump and micron gauge — NOT a manifold gauge, it's not precise enough. Hold for 15 minutes. If it rises above 500, you have a ..."},
        {q:"A multi-zone system with 3 indoor heads only cools 2 rooms effectively. The third is always warm. Diagnosis?",a:"Systematic approach: 1) Check airflow — is the filter clean? Is the head mounted correctly with no obstructions? 2) Check the refrigerant distribution — multi-zone systems use a branch box or indiv..."},
        {q:"What are the most common warranty-voiding installation mistakes on mini-splits?",a:"1) Not pulling a proper vacuum — moisture in the system causes acid formation that corrodes the compressor. Every manufacturer requires vacuum to 500 microns minimum. 2) Incorrect flare connections..."},
        {q:"How do you present the Good/Better/Best for a mini-split sale in a bonus room with no ductwork?",a:"Good ($3,800-4,500): Single-zone 12,000 BTU wall-mounted unit, standard efficiency (20 SEER), basic remote control, 10-year compressor warranty. Cools and heats the room independently. Better ($5,5..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A mini-split indoor unit is icing up on the evaporator coil in cooling mode. The filter is clean. Walk through the advanced diagnostic.",a:"With a clean filter eliminated: 1) CHECK REFRIGERANT CHARGE: Connect gauges. Low suction pressure = low evaporator saturation temperature = coil drops below 32°F = ice forms. On a 12K BTU unit, suc..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the inverter compressor technology in mini-splits. Why does this matter for diagnostics vs. conventional systems?",a:"Inverter technology: Instead of cycling ON/OFF at fixed speed, an inverter compressor uses a variable-frequency drive (VFD) to adjust compressor speed from ~15 Hz to 120 Hz (15-120% capacity). It r..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A 3-zone multi-split system works fine with 2 heads running but short-cycles when all 3 heads call simultaneously. What's the issue?",a:"This is a capacity management problem. Multi-split systems have a 'connection ratio' — the sum of indoor unit capacities vs. the outdoor unit capacity. Example: Three 12,000 BTU heads = 36,000 BTU ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the correct vacuum and pressure test procedure for a mini-split with a 50-foot line set? Why is this different from a standard short run?",a:"Standard short runs (under 25 feet) on pre-charged systems: some installers skip the vacuum and just purge with refrigerant. This is BAD practice but common. On a 50-foot line set, it's ABSOLUTELY ... liquid line). So 50 feet = 25 extra feet × 0.6 oz = 15 oz (almost 1 lb) additional R-410A. Weigh it in with a digital scale — do NOT estimate. 3) PRESSURE TEST: After charging, leak-check every flare, connection, and braze joint with electronic detector AND bubble solution. On 50 feet of line set, you have more joints and more potential leak points. A slow leak on a long run may not show low charge for months — then the customer calls with an icing complaint in July. 4) Document the charge weight, line set length, vacuum level, and hold time on the commissioning form. This is your warranty defense."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A Mitsubishi mini-split displays a blinking green light and won't start. The customer says it stopped working after a power outage. Troubleshoot.",a:"Mitsubishi blinking green light = communication error between indoor and outdoor units, OR a power/control board issue. Post-power-outage diagnosis: 1) RESET: Kill power at the breaker for 60 secon..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Compare wall-mounted, ceiling cassette, floor-mounted, and ducted mini-split indoor unit types. When do you specify each?",a:"WALL-MOUNTED: Most common residential. Mounts 7+ feet high on an exterior or interior wall. Best for: bedrooms, living rooms, offices. Pros: cheapest, easiest install, good air distribution on one ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What are the most common refrigerant line set installation errors that lead to warranty-voiding compressor failure within the first 2 years?",a:"Compressor failures in the first 2 years are almost always installation-caused: 1) MOISTURE IN THE SYSTEM: Failure to pull a proper vacuum (or not pulling one at all on short runs). Moisture + R-41... liquid line when the manufacturer spec calls for 3/8\" creates a restriction that starves the evaporator and overworks the compressor. Every one of these is a tech error that costs $2,000-4,000 to fix and destroys customer trust. Do it right the first time."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A multi-zone mini-split system shows error code P1 (high pressure protection) on the outdoor unit during heating mode in winter. What's the diagnosis?",a:"High pressure protection during HEATING mode means the outdoor unit's condenser (which acts as the evaporator in heat mode) is unable to reject heat effectively. In heating mode, the refrigerant cy..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: How do you calculate the heating load for a mini-split application in Northern Colorado, accounting for the extreme cold design temperature?",a:"Step 1: Determine the design heating temperature. For Greeley, CO: 99% design temp = -3°F (ASHRAE data). This means the system must heat the space when it's -3°F outside. Step 2: Calculate the heat..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the correct procedure for adding refrigerant charge to a mini-split system with a line set longer than the pre-charged length?",a:"Mini-split outdoor units come pre-charged for a standard line set length (typically 25 feet). If the actual line set is longer, you must ADD refrigerant to compensate. Procedure: 1) CHECK THE NAMEP... liquid line on a 12K BTU unit. 2) CALCULATE THE ADDITIONAL CHARGE: If the actual line set is 40 feet: Extra length = 40 - 25 = 15 feet. Additional charge = 15 × 0.6 oz = 9 oz. 3) WEIGH IN THE CHARGE — use a digital refrigerant scale. Connect the R-410A cylinder (upside down for liquid charging) to the suction service port. With the system running in cooling mode, slowly add refrigerant in liquid form through the suction port (the metering device will flash it to vapor before the compressor). 4) VERIFY — measure subcooling (should be 10-12°F) and superheat (10-15°F at the evaporator outlet). If subcooling is low after adding the calculated charge, there may be a leak or the system wasn't fully evacuated. CRITICAL: On short line sets (under 25 feet), the system is OVERCHARGED with the factory charge. Some manufacturers require recovering excess charge for short runs. Check the installation manual — overcharging raises head pressure, reduces efficiency, and can damage the compressor. For line sets under 15 feet, many manufacturers specify removing 0.6 oz per foot UNDER the pre-charged length. This is the #1 installation error on mini-splits — techs either ignore the charge adjustment entirely or don't know how to calculate it."}
      ]},
    {id:10,name:"Gas Line Leak Detection & Repair",category:"Gas",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the two approved methods for gas leak detection and when do you use each?",a:"1) Electronic combustible gas detector — sweep all accessible gas fittings, connections, valves, and the meter. The detector beeps/reads ppm. Use this for initial broad sweep of the system. 2) Gas ..."},
        {q:"You detect a gas leak at a customer's home. Walk through the exact protocol.",a:"1) Do NOT operate any electrical switches, light switches, or anything that creates a spark. 2) Open windows and doors for ventilation. 3) If the smell is strong, evacuate immediately and call 911 ..."},
        {q:"What is the pressure test requirement for new gas line installations in Colorado?",a:"Per Colorado Fuel Gas Code: test at 3 PSI (which is much higher than operating pressure of 7\" WC) for a minimum of 15 minutes with no pressure drop. Use a calibrated pressure gauge readable to 1/10 PSI. The test medium must be air or nitrogen — NEVER use gas to pressure test. All connections must be accessible during test. After passing, purge the line with gas until all air is expelled before lighting appliances. Document the test with date, time, starting pressure, ending pressure, and duration."},
        {q:"A customer says 'I smell gas sometimes near the stove but it goes away.' What do you do?",a:"This is NEVER 'nothing.' Respond with urgency: 'I want to check that right away — intermittent gas smells often indicate a small leak that could get worse. Let me do a full gas safety inspection of..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're pressure testing a new gas line at 3 PSI and the gauge drops 0.2 PSI over 15 minutes. Does this pass or fail? What variables can cause pressure fluctuation that isn't a leak?",a:"This FAILS. The code requires ZERO pressure drop over 15 minutes. However, before tearing apart joints: 1) TEMPERATURE CHANGE: Gas (air/nitrogen in the test) obeys Gay-Lussac's Law — pressure chang..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the differences between black iron pipe, CSST (corrugated stainless steel), and copper for gas line installation. When do you specify each?",a:"BLACK IRON (STEEL): The traditional standard. Threaded connections with pipe dope or yellow Teflon tape. Pros: extremely durable, proven track record, inexpensive material. Cons: labor-intensive (c..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A home has 5 gas appliances. Size the gas piping system from the meter to each appliance using the longest-length method.",a:"Appliances and BTU demands: Furnace (80,000), Water Heater (40,000), Range (65,000), Dryer (35,000), Fireplace (30,000). Total: 250,000 BTU. LONGEST-LENGTH METHOD: 1) Identify the longest run from ... WC pressure drop): At 80 feet equivalent length: 3/4\" pipe = 138,000 BTU capacity. 1\" pipe = 273,000 BTU. 1-1/4\" = 471,000 BTU. 4) MAIN LINE from meter: total demand = 250,000 BTU at 80 feet → 1\" pipe required (273,000 > 250,000). 5) BRANCH to furnace (80,000 BTU): if the branch is only 10 feet from the tee, you still size at 80 feet equivalent for safety. 3/4\" at 80 feet = 138,000 > 80,000 → 3/4\" is adequate. 6) Each branch is sized individually using the total run length to that appliance. COMMON MISTAKE: sizing branches by branch length only (10 feet from the tee). This ignores the pressure drop from the meter to the tee. ALWAYS size from the meter. When in doubt, upsize — a 1\" pipe costs $3/foot more than 3/4\" but prevents starvation issues for the life of the home."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You discover a gas leak at a union connection inside a wall. The homeowner wants you to just tighten it. Why is this unacceptable and what's the proper repair?",a:"Why tightening is unacceptable: 1) You can't verify the repair without a pressure test, and you can't pressure test a connection you can't access. 2) Union connections inside walls are a code viola..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A gas pressure test holds at 3 PSI for 15 minutes on a new gas line, but the customer reports intermittent gas smell after the system is in service. What could cause this?",a:"A system that passes a 3 PSI pressure test but leaks at operating pressure (7\" WC = 0.25 PSI) seems contradictory, but it happens. Causes: 1) THREAD SEALANT FAILURE UNDER THERMAL CYCLING — the joint was tight at test temperature but the repeated heating/cooling of gas appliances causes expansion/contraction that eventually works the joint loose. More common with Teflon tape than pipe dope — use both on critical joints. 2) FLEX CONNECTOR FITTING — CSST or appliance flex connectors can have slow leaks at the flare or compression fitting that only manifest when the fitting is warm. Retighten and retest. 3) APPLIANCE GAS VALVE — the appliance itself has an internal leak. Isolate: close the manual shutoff to each appliance one at a time and check for smell. 4) VALVE PACKING — older ball valves or gate valves can leak through the stem packing. Apply leak detection solution to the valve stem while the gas is flowing. 5) METER OR REGULATOR — the utility-side regulator can vent small amounts of gas during regulation. This is normal but alarming to customers. Distinguish by location of the smell. CRITICAL PROTOCOL: even after the system passed the pressure test, if the customer reports a gas smell, you MUST return and perform a comprehensive leak check with electronic detection AND bubble solution on EVERY joint and component in the system. Document everything."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the differences between natural gas, LP gas, and their implications for gas line sizing, appliance conversion, and safety.",a:"Natural gas: Methane (CH4). Specific gravity 0.60 (lighter than air — rises). Operating pressure: 7\" WC (residential). Heat content: ~1,000 BTU per cubic foot. LP gas (propane): C3H8. Specific gravity 1.52 (HEAVIER than air — sinks and pools in low areas). Operating pressure: 11\" WC (residential). Heat content: ~2,500 BTU per cubic foot. Implications: 1) GAS LINE SIZING: LP delivers 2.5x more BTU per cubic foot, so smaller pipe sizes are acceptable for the same BTU load. But most sizing tables are for natural gas — use the LP-specific tables. 2) APPLIANCE CONVERSION: Changing from natural gas to LP requires: new orifices (LP orifices are smaller because the gas is denser and higher pressure), gas valve adjustment from 7\" to 11\" WC manifold pressure, and conversion of the regulator. Using natural gas orifices on LP = severe overfiring, flame rollout, potential explosion. 3) SAFETY: LP is MORE dangerous — it's heavier than air, pools in basements and crawlspaces, and has a lower explosive limit (2.1% vs 5% for natural gas). LP leaks in basements are potential explosion hazards. Detectors must be placed LOW for LP, HIGH for natural gas. 4) LP requires an external storage tank with specific setback requirements from structures."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're running a new gas line for a pool heater located 80 feet from the gas meter. Size the gas line for a 400,000 BTU pool heater.",a:"Step-by-step using IFGC gas pipe sizing tables: 1) Determine total BTU demand: 400,000 BTU. 2) Determine equivalent length: 80 feet + fittings. Assume four 90° elbows at 5 feet equivalent each = 80... WC drop. 4) Reference Table 402.4 (Schedule 40 metallic pipe): At 100 feet, 0.5\" WC drop: 1\" pipe = 175,000 BTU (not enough), 1-1/4\" pipe = 360,000 BTU (not enough), 1-1/2\" pipe = 625,000 BTU (adequate). You need 1-1/2\" pipe for this run. BUT ALSO: verify the METER capacity — a standard residential gas meter is typically rated for 250-400 CFH (250,000-400,000 BTU). Adding a 400,000 BTU pool heater to a home that already has a furnace (80,000 BTU), water heater (40,000 BTU), range (65,000 BTU) = 585,000 BTU total demand. The meter may need to be upgraded by the utility company — call the gas company BEFORE you run the line. The total demand must also be sized FROM THE METER through every branch to every appliance. This is master plumber-level gas pipe design."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Describe the proper procedure for purging a gas line after new installation. What are the hazards of improper purging?",a:"After a gas line passes the pressure test (performed with air or nitrogen — NEVER gas), you must purge the air from the line before lighting appliances. Procedure: 1) VERIFY the pressure test passe..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer wants a gas line run to a new outdoor grill, fire pit, and patio heater — all on the same line. How do you design and size this system?",a:"This is a manifold design problem. Step 1: Determine individual BTU demands — Grill: typically 40,000-60,000 BTU. Fire pit: 40,000-90,000 BTU. Patio heater: 40,000-50,000 BTU. Use manufacturer spec... pipe (reference table). Each branch at 10 feet can drop to 3/4\" for 50,000-90,000 BTU loads. Step 5: Install a manual shutoff valve for each appliance AND a master shutoff near the house. Step 6: Install quick-disconnect fittings for the grill if it's not permanently plumbed. Step 7: Verify the gas meter can handle the additional load (add to existing house demand). Step 8: Pull the permit, pass the pressure test, purge, and document. Present: 'Running all three on one professionally designed gas line costs less than three separate runs and gives you a single shutoff for the whole patio setup.'"}
      ]},
    {id:11,name:"Membership Sales Training",category:"Sales",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the three JT Plumbing membership tiers and what does each include?",a:"Silver ($14.99/mo): Annual plumbing inspection, 10% off all repairs, priority scheduling, no diagnostic fee. Gold ($24.99/mo): Everything in Silver PLUS annual HVAC tune-up, 15% off all repairs, 1 ..."},
        {q:"What's the script for introducing memberships during a service call?",a:"After diagnosing the issue and before presenting pricing: 'Before I show you the options, I want to mention something that could save you money today AND long-term. We have a membership program tha..."},
        {q:"A customer says 'I don't need a membership, I'll just call you when something breaks.' Best response?",a:"'Totally understand — and that's what most people think until the first emergency. Here's the thing: the customers who call us at 2 AM with a burst pipe or a dead furnace on Christmas Eve? 90% of t..."},
        {q:"What's the membership conversion rate target and how do you track it?",a:"Target: present to 100% of customers, convert 1 in 5 (20%). Track in the pricebook under My Numbers — membership presentations and conversions are two of the 9 KPIs. Top performers convert 30-35%. ..."},
        {q:"How do you present the membership so the discount applies to TODAY's repair?",a:"'Let me show you something — if you join our Gold membership today at $24.99/month, you instantly get 15% off this repair. On a $1,200 job, that's $180 savings. The membership pays for itself in th..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer signed up for Gold membership 4 months ago and now wants to cancel because 'they haven't used it.' How do you retain them?",a:"Retention script: 'I totally understand — let me pull up your account and show you what you've already received.' Then itemize: 'In 4 months, you've saved $X on the repair we did, you have your ann..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the lifetime value (LTV) of a Gold membership customer vs. a non-member customer over 5 years. Why does this matter for your commission?",a:"NON-MEMBER (5 years): Average 1.5 service calls per year × $450 average ticket = $675/year × 5 years = $3,375 total revenue. No predictable recurring revenue. Each call requires marketing spend to ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A property manager with 12 rental units asks about a bulk membership discount. How do you structure this deal?",a:"Property managers are GOLD — recurring revenue at scale. Structure: 'For 12+ units, we offer our Property Management Partner Program: 1) Rate: $19.99/unit/month (20% discount from standard Gold at ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Design the perfect 'membership save' when a customer calls to cancel because they're on a fixed income.",a:"Fixed-income customers are the most price-sensitive but also the most vulnerable to expensive emergency repairs. Save script: 'I completely understand being careful with your budget — that\'s smart..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What KPIs should the service manager track weekly for the membership program?",a:"Weekly membership dashboard: 1) NEW SIGN-UPS this week (target: 8-12 per week company-wide, ~2 per tech). 2) CANCELLATIONS this week (target: <3% monthly churn). 3) ASK RATE: % of completed calls w..."}
      ]},
    {id:12,name:"Objection Handling & Closing",category:"Sales",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"Customer says 'That's too expensive.' What's the JT framework for responding?",a:"The LAER framework: Listen — 'I hear you, and I appreciate you being upfront about that.' Acknowledge — 'Nobody wants to spend more than they need to. That's completely fair.' Explore — 'Help me un..."},
        {q:"Customer says 'Let me get another quote.' How do you handle this without being pushy?",a:"'Absolutely — you should feel confident in your decision. That's exactly why I showed you three options at different price points. While you're getting other quotes, a few things to compare: Are th..."},
        {q:"Customer says 'I need to talk to my spouse.' What do you do?",a:"This is the #1 objection in residential service. Response: 'Of course — this is a big decision and you want to make it together. Let me help you have that conversation.' Then: 1) 'What questions do..."},
        {q:"You've presented Good/Better/Best and the customer says 'Just do the Good option.' Should you push for Better?",a:"NO. Never make the customer feel bad about choosing Good. Say: 'Great choice — Good is solid and it's going to solve your problem today. Let me get started.' The customer chose from the options YOU..."},
        {q:"What's the same-day close technique for larger jobs ($3,000+)?",a:"The 'Already Here' close: 'I know this is a significant investment. Here's the thing — I'm already here, I've already diagnosed everything, and I can answer every question you have face to face. If..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Customer says 'I found the same part on Amazon for $30. You're charging me $185.' How do you handle the parts markup objection?",a:"This is the #2 objection after 'too expensive.' Script: 'You\'re absolutely right — you can buy that part online for less. Here\'s what that $185 includes that Amazon doesn\'t: 1) I verified this i..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You've presented three options and the customer says 'I need to think about it' and walks you to the door. What's the last-resort save?",a:"The 'Columbo Close' — named after the detective who always had 'one more thing.' As you\'re walking to the door, pause and say: 'You know what, before I go — I want to make sure I did my job today...."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer is comparing your quote to a lowball competitor. They show you the competitor's quote at 40% less. How do you handle this without discounting?",a:"NEVER match or beat — this destroys your margin and sets a precedent. Instead, DECODE the competitor\'s quote: 'I appreciate you showing me this — let me help you compare apples to apples. May I?' ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: The customer agrees to the work but then says 'Can you give me a cash discount?' What's the policy and how do you respond?",a:"JT Plumbing policy: NO cash discounts. Here\'s why, and how to handle it: Cash discounts create: 1) Tax compliance issues — all revenue must be reported regardless of payment method. 2) Margin eros..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're in a home where both spouses are present but they clearly disagree — one wants to do the work and the other is resistant. How do you navigate this without taking sides?",a:"This is a COUPLES DYNAMICS situation — read the room. Rules: 1) NEVER take sides. If one spouse says 'See? I told you we needed this!' — don\'t agree or disagree. Stay neutral: 'It\'s a great quest..."}
      ]},
    {id:13,name:"Option Card Presentation",category:"Sales",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What is the correct ORDER to present Good/Better/Best options and why?",a:"Present Best FIRST, then Better, then Good. Why? Anchoring psychology. When the customer sees Best at $4,500 first, the Better option at $3,200 feels reasonable, and Good at $1,800 feels like a bar..."},
        {q:"How should the option cards look when you show them to the customer on the tablet?",a:"1) Clean, professional, branded with JT Plumbing colors. 2) Each option shows: tier name, itemized scope of work, warranty details, total price, and monthly financing payment. 3) The Best option sh..."},
        {q:"A customer is looking at the options and goes silent. What do you do?",a:"NOTHING. Let them think. Silence is your best friend. The biggest mistake techs make is filling the silence with discounts, extra explanations, or nervous talking. The customer is processing. Give ..."},
        {q:"What percentage of customers should choose Best, Better, and Good in a well-presented sale?",a:"Industry target with good presentation: 25-30% Best, 45-55% Better, 20-25% Good. If more than 40% of your customers choose Good, your Best option might be priced too high or you're not explaining t..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You notice that 65% of your customers are choosing Good tier. What does this indicate about your presentation, and how do you adjust?",a:"65% Good means the value proposition of Better and Best isn\'t landing. Root causes: 1) PRICE ANCHORING FAILURE: You might be presenting Good first (lowest to highest). This anchors on the cheap op..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer is an engineer and wants to see the technical specifications, not just the price tiers. How do you adjust your presentation style?",a:"Engineers and analytical customers are a GIFT if you handle them right — they\'ll choose Best or Better every time because the DATA supports it. Adjustments: 1) SLOW DOWN and go deep on specs. Show..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: How do you modify the Good/Better/Best presentation for a landlord vs. a homeowner?",a:"Landlords have COMPLETELY different motivations than homeowners. Landlord priorities: 1) Minimize cost. 2) Minimize callbacks. 3) Keep tenants happy (to reduce turnover). 4) Speed — every day the u..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: When presenting on the tablet, what visual layout and information hierarchy gets the highest Better/Best selection rate?",a:"Based on industry conversion data, the optimal option card layout: 1) THREE COLUMNS side by side — Good on the left, Better center, Best on the right. The eye naturally gravitates to center. 2) BET..."}
      ]},
    {id:14,name:"Confined Space Entry",category:"Safety",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What is the definition of a confined space in plumbing/HVAC work and give three examples?",a:"A confined space has: 1) Large enough to enter and perform work. 2) Limited or restricted means of entry or exit. 3) Not designed for continuous occupancy. Plumbing examples: 1) Utility vaults and ..."},
        {q:"What atmospheric testing is required before entering a confined space?",a:"Test for three things in this order: 1) Oxygen levels — must be between 19.5% and 23.5%. Below 19.5% is oxygen-deficient and immediately dangerous to life. 2) Flammable gases — must be below 10% of..."},
        {q:"You need to enter a crawlspace to repair a water line. What's the minimum safety protocol?",a:"1) Tell someone — never enter alone. A coworker or the homeowner must know you're going in and have eyes on the access point. 2) Test the air if there's any indication of gas, sewage, or poor venti..."},
        {q:"What is the difference between a confined space and a permit-required confined space?",a:"A regular confined space meets the three basic criteria (enterable, limited access, not for continuous occupancy). A PERMIT-REQUIRED confined space has those PLUS at least one additional hazard: 1)..."},
        {q:"You arrive at a crawlspace entry and notice standing water. What do you assess before entering?",a:"Standing water in a crawlspace creates multiple hazards: 1) Electrical — is there any wiring, junction boxes, or equipment in or near the water? Test for stray voltage with a non-contact voltage te..."},
        {q:"Your coworker enters a crawlspace and stops responding to your calls. What is the rescue protocol?",a:"DO NOT ENTER AFTER THEM. This is the #1 cause of multiple fatalities in confined spaces — the would-be rescuer becomes a second victim. Protocol: 1) Call 911 immediately — tell them 'confined space..."},
        {q:"What PPE and equipment should be staged at the entry point before anyone enters a confined space?",a:"Stage BEFORE entry: 1) 4-gas monitor (O2, LEL, CO, H2S) with fresh calibration. 2) Ventilation fan — forced-air ventilation into the space. 3) Full-body harness with retrieval line for the entrant...."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're in a crawlspace and your 4-gas monitor alarms for H2S at 12 PPM. What is H2S, why is it dangerous at this level, and what's the immediate action protocol?",a:"H2S (hydrogen sulfide) is produced by decomposing organic matter in sewer systems. At low concentrations it smells like rotten eggs, but at higher levels it deadens your sense of smell — you can't ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is oxygen displacement and why is it especially dangerous in confined spaces with gas appliances?",a:"Oxygen displacement occurs when another gas (methane, CO2, nitrogen, propane) accumulates and physically displaces oxygen in a confined area. Normal atmosphere is 20.9% O2. Effects of reduced O2: 1..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the gas stratification principle and how it affects atmospheric testing in confined spaces at different heights.",a:"Gases stratify based on their vapor density relative to air (air = 1.0). Lighter-than-air gases rise to the TOP: Methane (CH4) = 0.55 — natural gas, found in sewer systems. Hydrogen (H2) = 0.07. He... from ceiling), middle (breathing zone), and bottom (6\" from floor). A reading at waist height may show safe while the floor has lethal H2S or the ceiling has explosive methane. In sewer manholes, always test BOTTOM FIRST — H2S kills at the entry point before you even get fully inside. In a mechanical room with a gas leak, methane accumulates at the ceiling where ignition sources (lights, pilot lights) are located. The bottom may read safe while the ceiling is at explosive levels. This is why multi-level testing is not optional — it's physics."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A utility crew is working in the street and you need to access a sewer manhole near their excavation. What permits and procedures apply under OSHA 1910.146?",a:"OSHA 1910.146 (Permit-Required Confined Spaces) applies. Full procedure: 1) ENTRY PERMIT must be completed BEFORE entry. It documents: space location, purpose of entry, authorized entrants, attenda..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What are the specific biological hazards present in sewer-related confined spaces, and what vaccinations and post-exposure protocols apply?",a:"Biological hazards in sewer environments: 1) BACTERIA: E. coli, Salmonella, Leptospira (from rat urine — causes leptospirosis), Campylobacter. Entry through cuts, mouth, eyes. 2) VIRUSES: Hepatitis..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're called to repair a water line in a crawlspace. Upon arrival, you notice the crawlspace has no vapor barrier, visible mold on the joists, and 2 inches of standing water. Create a complete hazard assessment before entry.",a:"Complete hazard assessment (document on the entry checklist before going in): ATMOSPHERIC: 1) Standing water + organic material = potential methane, H2S generation. Test with 4-gas monitor at openi..."}
      ]},
    {id:15,name:"Fall Protection / Ladder Safety",category:"Safety",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the three-point contact rules for ladder use and what's the #1 cause of ladder injuries in the trades?",a:"Three-point contact: maintain two hands and one foot, OR two feet and one hand on the ladder at all times while climbing. Never carry tools in your hands while climbing — use a tool belt or rope to..."},
        {q:"When is fall protection equipment required for HVAC rooftop work?",a:"OSHA requires fall protection at 6 feet for general industry work. For rooftop HVAC units: if you're within 6 feet of an unprotected roof edge while working, you need either a guardrail, safety net..."},
        {q:"You arrive at a job and need to access a rooftop AC unit. The homeowner offers you their personal ladder. What do you do?",a:"Politely decline: 'I appreciate the offer, but for your safety and ours, we're required to use our own equipment that's been inspected and rated for commercial use. I've got everything I need in th..."},
        {q:"What should you do before climbing on a customer's roof for the first time?",a:"Before feet leave the ground: 1) Walk the perimeter on the ground — look for obvious damage, sagging, or soft spots. 2) Ask the customer: 'When was the roof last replaced? Any soft spots or leaks y..."},
        {q:"You're working in an attic and need to walk across ceiling joists. What's the fall prevention protocol?",a:"Attic work is one of the most dangerous residential environments. Protocol: 1) NEVER step between joists — you WILL go through the ceiling. Walk ONLY on joists or lay down plywood walkways. 2) Illu..."},
        {q:"During a routine check, you notice one rung is bent on the company extension ladder. What do you do?",a:"DO NOT USE THE LADDER. Not even if the bent rung is one you 'don't need to step on.' Protocol: 1) Tag the ladder with a red 'DO NOT USE' tag immediately. 2) Report it to the office — it needs to be..."},
        {q:"What are the most common ladder-related injuries in the trades and how do you prevent each one?",a:"1) Falls from height (most common, most severe) — caused by overreaching, carrying tools while climbing, or poor setup angle. Prevention: follow 4:1 rule, maintain 3-point contact, use a tool belt ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the fall arrest distance for a technician wearing a 6-foot lanyard with a deceleration device, connected to an anchor point at foot level. Will a 12-foot clearance below the anchor be sufficient?",a:"Total fall distance calculation: 1) Free fall distance = 6 feet (lanyard length). OSHA limits free fall to 6 feet max. 2) Deceleration distance = 3.5 feet (maximum allowed by OSHA — the shock absor..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You need to service a rooftop AC unit on a commercial building with no existing anchor points. What temporary anchor options are OSHA-compliant?",a:"OSHA requires fall protection anchor points to withstand 5,000 lbs per worker (or be designed by a qualified person for 2x the intended load). Options for rooftops without permanent anchors: 1) POR... thick concrete or reinforced CMU). 3) ROOF HATCH ANCHOR: Mounts to the roof hatch frame — worker clips in immediately upon emerging. 4) TEMPORARY HORIZONTAL LIFELINE: Stretched between two structural anchor points, allows worker to move laterally along the roof edge. Requires engineered installation. 5) WARNING LINE SYSTEM: Not a fall arrest but a fall prevention — stanchions and rope/wire set back 6 feet from the edge. Worker stays inside the warning line and doesn't need a harness. Only valid if ALL work can be performed 6+ feet from any edge. For JT Plumbing: if a rooftop has no anchor points and the work requires edge proximity, the job gets flagged for a site safety assessment before dispatch. Never improvise anchor points — they must be rated."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the OSHA hierarchy of fall protection and in what order should controls be implemented?",a:"OSHA's hierarchy of fall protection (in order of preference): 1) ELIMINATION: Can we do the work from the ground? Use a lift, extension tools, or ground-level access. Best option — no fall risk at ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A technician falls while wearing a harness and is hanging suspended from the anchor point. He's conscious but can't reach anything. What is suspension trauma and what's the rescue time limit?",a:"Suspension trauma (orthostatic intolerance/harness hang syndrome): When a person hangs motionless in a harness, the leg straps compress the femoral veins, causing blood to pool in the legs. Without..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're conducting a weekly ladder inspection. What specific components do you check and what are the rejection criteria?",a:"Inspection checklist (document and date each inspection): SIDE RAILS: 1) Check for cracks, bends, dents, or corrosion. Any crack = immediate removal from service. 2) Check fiberglass for weathering..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the difference between a Type I, Type IA, Type IAA, Type II, and Type III ladder? Which does JT Plumbing require and why?",a:"Ladder duty ratings by type: Type III (Light Duty): 200 lb capacity. Household use only. NOT acceptable for commercial/trade work. Type II (Medium Duty): 225 lb capacity. Light commercial — painter..."}
      ]},
    {id:16,name:"Lockout / Tagout Procedures",category:"Safety",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"When must you perform lockout/tagout during plumbing and HVAC work?",a:"Any time you're servicing equipment where unexpected energization could cause injury: 1) Before working inside an electrical panel or on wiring. 2) Before changing a garbage disposal or well pump. ..."},
        {q:"Describe the correct lockout/tagout procedure for replacing an electric water heater element.",a:"1) Go to the breaker panel, turn off the 30A double-pole breaker for the water heater. 2) Apply your personal padlock to the breaker (use a breaker lockout device). 3) Attach your tag with your nam..."},
        {q:"The homeowner says 'Just flip the switch on the wall, you don't need to lock the breaker.' Why is this wrong?",a:"A wall switch is NOT a lockout point. Reasons: 1) Anyone can flip it back on — a family member, a child, even the homeowner forgetting you're working. 2) Wall switches can fail — the contacts can w..."},
        {q:"You're working on a garbage disposal and the homeowner's child is in the kitchen. What extra precautions do you take?",a:"1) Lock out at the breaker — not just the wall switch. Kids are curious and may flip switches. 2) Place your lockout tag on the switch as a secondary visual warning. 3) Unplug the unit if it's a pl..."},
        {q:"What is 'try before you lock' and why is it important?",a:"'Try before you lock' means: AFTER you lock out the breaker, go back to the equipment and TRY to start it. Press the thermostat, flip the switch, push the button — whatever normally activates it. I..."},
        {q:"Two JT Plumbing experts are working on the same piece of equipment. How does LOTO work with multiple people?",a:"EACH person applies their OWN lock and tag. Use a multi-lock hasp that allows multiple padlocks on the same lockout point. The equipment CANNOT be re-energized until EVERY lock is removed. Rules: 1..."},
        {q:"Beyond electrical, what other energy sources require lockout during plumbing and HVAC work?",a:"Lockout applies to ALL energy sources, not just electrical: 1) Gas — close and lock the gas valve before working on gas appliances. Use a valve lockout device. 2) Water pressure — close the shut-of..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You need to replace a blower motor in a furnace that's hardwired (no plug). The breaker panel is in a locked utility room and the building manager won't be back for 2 hours. What do you do?",a:"You WAIT. Period. There is no scenario where you work on energized 240V equipment because the lockout point is inconvenient. Alternatives before waiting: 1) Call the building manager — explain it's..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between lockout and tagout. When is tagout alone sufficient, and when is a lock mandatory?",a:"LOCKOUT: A physical locking device (padlock) placed on an energy isolation device (breaker, valve, disconnect) that PHYSICALLY PREVENTS re-energization. Only the person who placed the lock has the ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're working on an HVAC system and you've locked out the breaker. The system also has a 24V transformer powering the thermostat circuit. Is the 24V side a hazard?",a:"24V won't kill you, but it CAN cause problems: 1) 24V can deliver enough current to create an arc if wires touch metal — in the presence of gas vapors, this is an ignition source. 2) A short on the..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Describe the OSHA-required procedure for removing someone else's lock in an emergency (orphaned lock removal).",a:"OSHA 1910.147(e)(3) — Authorized lock removal by someone other than the lock owner. This is ONLY done when the employee who placed the lock is not available and cannot be reached. Steps: 1) VERIFY:..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A commercial HVAC rooftop unit has a gas supply, three electrical circuits (compressor, controls, economizer), and a pneumatic damper system. Create a complete LOTO plan.",a:"Complete LOTO plan for RTU with multiple energy sources: ELECTRICAL (3 lockout points): 1) Compressor circuit (208/230V, 3-phase): Lock breaker at electrical panel, apply lock + tag. Verify 0V at c..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What are the OSHA recordkeeping requirements if a lockout/tagout procedure is violated and what are the potential penalties for JT Plumbing?",a:"OSHA Recordkeeping: 1) Any injury resulting from LOTO violation is recordable on the OSHA 300 Log if it requires medical treatment beyond first aid, involves lost workdays, or results in death. 2) ..."}
      ]},
    {id:17,name:"PPE Requirements & Usage",category:"Safety",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What PPE is required for each type of service call at JT Plumbing?",a:"Standard every call: safety glasses, work gloves, steel/composite toe boots. Drain/Sewer: ADD full face shield, heavy rubber gloves, waterproof apron/coveralls. Soldering/brazing: ADD fire-resistan..."},
        {q:"A customer says 'You don't need all that safety stuff, it's just a simple repair.' How do you respond?",a:"'I appreciate that — and you're right, this is a straightforward job. But at JT Plumbing, we treat every job the same when it comes to safety. These glasses protect my eyes from debris, these glove..."},
        {q:"What should you do if you discover mold or asbestos during a service call?",a:"STOP WORK IMMEDIATELY. Do not disturb the material. For suspected asbestos (common in older homes in pipe insulation, duct tape, floor tiles): 1) Back away. 2) Inform the customer: 'I've found mate..."},
        {q:"What respiratory protection is required for different plumbing and HVAC scenarios?",a:"N95 disposable respirator: Crawlspaces with dust/insulation, light mold presence, cutting drywall or concrete. N100/P100 half-face respirator: Heavy mold exposure, working near disturbed insulation..."},
        {q:"You're soldering copper pipe in a wall cavity near wood framing. What fire safety PPE and procedures apply?",a:"PPE: fire-resistant gloves, safety glasses with shade lens, long sleeves (cotton, not synthetic). Procedures: 1) Place a fire-resistant cloth or shield between the flame and all combustible materia..."},
        {q:"Your safety glasses are fogged up while working in a humid crawlspace. Can you remove them temporarily?",a:"NO. Fogged glasses are frustrating but removing eye protection is never acceptable. Solutions: 1) Apply anti-fog coating or use anti-fog safety glasses (JT Plumbing stocks these). 2) Ventilate the ..."},
        {q:"What is the minimum PPE required in the JT Plumbing truck at all times?",a:"Every truck must carry: 1) 2 pairs of safety glasses (primary + backup). 2) Cut-resistant work gloves. 3) Heavy rubber gloves (drain work). 4) Steel/composite toe boots (worn, not just carried). 5)..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're brazing a copper refrigerant line in a tight mechanical room. Describe every PPE and fire prevention measure, and explain the specific burn and fume hazards of brazing vs. soldering.",a:"Brazing vs. soldering hazards: Soldering uses temperatures around 450°F with tin-silver alloy — relatively low risk. Brazing uses an oxy-acetylene torch at 1,100-1,500°F with silver-bearing brazing... gauntlet style to protect forearms. 3) Long-sleeve cotton or FR clothing — NO synthetics (polyester melts into skin). 4) N95 or better respirator — fluoride fumes. In a tight room, ventilate with a fan or use a supplied-air respirator. Fire prevention: 5) Fire-resistant heat shield behind the joint (copper, ceramic, or wetted fire cloth). 6) Spray surrounding combustibles with water. 7) ABC fire extinguisher within arm's reach — not across the room. 8) Fire watch: after brazing, remain in the area for 30 minutes monitoring for smoldering. 9) Thermal camera check behind walls if the joint is near framing. 10) NEVER braze with refrigerant in the line — refrigerant decomposes at high temperatures into phosgene gas (chemical weapon). Evacuate the system COMPLETELY before applying heat."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the OSHA Noise Exposure Standard (1910.95) as it applies to plumbing and HVAC work. What tools exceed the permissible exposure limit?",a:"OSHA Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL): 90 dBA as an 8-hour time-weighted average (TWA). Action level (hearing conservation program required): 85 dBA TWA. Common plumbing/HVAC noise levels: Hydro je..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A technician reports a skin rash on his hands and forearms after performing drain work. What are the possible causes and what's the incident response?",a:"Possible causes (in order of likelihood): 1) CONTACT DERMATITIS from sewage bacteria or chemicals — most common in drain work. Sewage contains thousands of bacterial species that cause skin irritat..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is an SDS (Safety Data Sheet), where must they be kept, and how do you use one when a chemical exposure occurs?",a:"SDS (formerly MSDS) is a standardized 16-section document for every chemical product. OSHA Hazard Communication Standard (1910.1200) requires employers to maintain SDS for every chemical in the wor..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between N95, N100, P100, and supplied-air respirators. Which is required for each plumbing/HVAC scenario?",a:"Filter ratings: N = Not oil resistant. P = Oil Proof. 95 = filters 95% of airborne particles. 100 = filters 99.97% (HEPA equivalent). N95: Adequate for: dust, drywall cutting, light mold, general c..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: It's July in Greeley, 98°F outside. You have a tech working on a rooftop AC unit in full PPE. Describe the heat illness progression, recognition signs, and prevention protocol.",a:"Heat illness progression: 1) HEAT CRAMPS: Muscle cramps from electrolyte loss through sweat. First warning sign. Move to shade, hydrate with electrolyte solution, rest. 2) HEAT EXHAUSTION: Heavy sw..."}
      ]},
    {id:18,name:"Customer Communication & De-escalation",category:"Sales",required:false,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"A customer is angry about a previous tech's work and is yelling when you arrive. What's the de-escalation protocol?",a:"HEAR Method: H — Hear them out. Let them vent for 60-90 seconds without interrupting. Nod, maintain eye contact, show you're listening. E — Empathize. 'I understand why you're frustrated. If this h..."},
        {q:"How do you communicate bad news — like a $8,000 sewer replacement — to a homeowner?",a:"The Sandwich Method: 1) GOOD NEWS first: 'I was able to get a clear picture of your entire sewer line, and the good news is the first 40 feet is in great shape.' 2) BAD NEWS with empathy: 'However,..."},
        {q:"What are the first 60 seconds at every customer's door supposed to look like?",a:"The JT Doorstep Protocol: 1) Arrive 5 min early, park on the street (not driveway). 2) Put on booties BEFORE knocking. 3) Smile, firm handshake: 'Hi, I'm [name] with JT Plumbing. Are you [customer ..."},
        {q:"The customer hovers over you while you work and asks questions about every step. How do you handle it?",a:"Welcome it. A curious customer is an engaged customer — and engaged customers buy more. Response: 'Great question — let me show you exactly what I'm seeing here.' Turn it into education: explain wh..."},
        {q:"You finish a job and the customer seems satisfied but doesn't mention a review. What's the script?",a:"The Natural Ask — timing is everything. Wait until AFTER they've expressed satisfaction (even a simple 'Looks great, thanks'). Then: 'I'm really glad we got this taken care of for you. Hey, can I a..."},
        {q:"A customer complains about wait time — they've been without hot water for 2 days waiting for their appointment. How do you handle it?",a:"Acknowledge and validate FIRST: 'Two days without hot water — I know that's been really uncomfortable for your family, and I'm sorry we couldn't get here sooner. The good news is I'm here now and I..."},
        {q:"You're at a customer's home and you need to use the bathroom. What's the protocol?",a:"Ask permission: 'Would you mind if I used your restroom?' If they say yes: 1) Remove booties/boots at the door — don't track anything. 2) Leave it cleaner than you found it. 3) Be quick — you're on..."},
        {q:"The customer tells you their previous plumber did the work for half your price. How do you respond without badmouthing the competition?",a:"Never trash talk. Script: 'I understand — price is important and I respect that you're doing your research. I can't speak to how other companies price their work, but I can tell you exactly what's ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You arrive at a home and realize the customer is elderly, lives alone, and seems confused about the plumbing issue. How do you adjust your approach to protect both the customer and the company?",a:"This requires heightened ethical awareness: 1) SLOW DOWN: Speak clearly, avoid jargon, and confirm understanding: 'I want to make sure I'm explaining this well. Does that make sense?' 2) SHOW EVIDE..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer posts on Nextdoor: 'JT Plumbing just tried to charge me $1,200 to fix a toilet. What a rip-off.' You know the job involved a flange rebuild, wax seal, supply line, and shut-off valve replacement. How does the company respond publicly?",a:"Public response (written by owner/manager, NOT the tech): 'Hi [Name], thank you for sharing your experience. We understand $1,200 feels significant for a toilet repair, and we want to address your ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're presenting a $6,500 sewer line repair to a customer who is visibly upset and mentions they just lost their job. How do you handle the conversation with empathy without compromising the sale or the urgency of the repair?",a:"Empathy FIRST, solutions SECOND: 'I'm really sorry to hear about your job situation. I know this repair couldn't come at a worse time, and I want to be completely transparent with you about what we..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A husband and wife are disagreeing about the repair in front of you. One wants to go with your recommendation and the other thinks it's too expensive. How do you navigate this?",a:"Rule #1: You are NOT a marriage counselor. Do NOT take sides. Strategy: 1) ADDRESS BOTH PEOPLE equally — make eye contact with both, direct your answers to both. Don't just talk to the one who's ag..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: During a job, you accidentally damage the customer's property — you knock a hole in drywall while pulling a water heater out, or scratch hardwood floors. What's the immediate protocol?",a:"OWN IT IMMEDIATELY. Never try to hide damage. Step 1: 'I want to let you know right away — when I was moving the water heater, I put a dent in your drywall. I'm sorry about that.' Step 2: PHOTOGRAP..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You discover a major safety hazard in the customer's home that isn't related to the job you were called for — exposed wiring, a gas leak from a different appliance, or a water heater venting into a bedroom closet. What's the ethical and legal obligation?",a:"You have BOTH an ethical AND legal obligation to inform the customer. Legal: In most jurisdictions, a licensed tradesperson who observes an imminent safety hazard has a duty to warn. Failure to war..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer demands a refund for work completed two weeks ago, claiming it 'didn't fix the problem.' They're threatening a BBB complaint and a lawsuit. How do you handle this?",a:"DE-ESCALATION + DOCUMENTATION: Phone response (office handles this, NOT the original tech): 'I understand you're frustrated, and I want to make sure we resolve this properly. Let me review your ser..."}
      ]},
    {id:19,name:"Drain Cleaning Fundamentals",category:"Drain/Sewer",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the three main methods of drain cleaning and when do you use each?",a:"1) Cable/Snake Machine — standard for most residential stoppages. Kitchen sinks, main lines, floor drains. Uses a rotating steel cable with a cutting head to break through blockages. Best for: root..."},
        {q:"A customer has a slow kitchen drain. Walk through the diagnosis before clearing.",a:"1) Ask questions first: 'When did it start? Both sides of the sink or just one? Any gurgling? Any other drains slow?' 2) Run water — observe how fast it drains. If it's completely stopped vs. slow ..."},
        {q:"What cable size and cutting head do you use for different drain sizes?",a:"Lavatory/tub drains (1.5-2 inch): 1/4\" or 5/16\" cable with small retriever or drop head. Kitchen drains (2 inch): 3/8\" cable with grease cutter head. Floor drains and 3-inch lines: 1/2\" or 5/8\" cable with spade or C-cutter. Main sewer lines (4-6 inch): 3/4\" or 7/8\" cable with root-cutting blade head. CRITICAL: never use a cable larger than the pipe — it will bind, kink, and potentially crack the pipe. Never use a powered machine on a P-trap — disconnect the trap and feed the cable directly into the wall. Common mistake: trying to clear a 1.5\" lavatory drain with a 3/4\" cable intended for a main line. That's how you crack the drain line inside the wall and turn a $250 job into a $2,500 job."},
        {q:"You clear a main line stoppage and pull back a root ball. What do you tell the customer?",a:"Show them the evidence: 'See these roots? This means tree roots have found their way into your sewer pipe through a joint or crack. I cleared it today, but roots grow back — typically within 6-12 m..."},
        {q:"What safety precautions are specific to drain cleaning work?",a:"1) ALWAYS wear face shield and rubber gloves — drain cables spin and throw debris. Sewage splashback carries hepatitis, E. coli, and other pathogens. 2) Secure the cable machine — foot on the frame..."},
        {q:"A customer wants you to pour chemical drain cleaner before you snake it. Why do you refuse?",a:"'I completely understand the thought, but I actually can't use chemical drain cleaners for three important reasons: 1) Safety — if I snake through a line full of sulfuric acid or lye, it splashes b..."},
        {q:"What's the Good/Better/Best presentation for a standard main line drain cleaning?",a:"Good ($345): Cable main line clear, verify flow restored, flush test. Gets you flowing today. Better ($595): Cable clear PLUS camera inspection — shows root intrusion, pipe condition, bellies, offs..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're clearing a main line and the cable suddenly stops advancing at 45 feet and the machine is straining. It won't go forward or back. Diagnose the situation and explain the recovery procedure.",a:"Cable stuck at 45 feet = one of three scenarios: 1) SEVERE ROOT BALL: The cable has wound into a dense root mass and the cutting head is tangled. Do NOT force it — you'll kink the cable ($300-500 r..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A restaurant owner calls with a grease-clogged main line. This is the third time in 6 months. Walk through the long-term solution beyond just clearing it again.",a:"Recurring grease blockage in a restaurant = systematic failure, not just a clog. Long-term approach: 1) IMMEDIATE: Hydro-jet the line (cable just punches through grease — it reforms in days). 2) IN... per foot) allows grease to solidify before exiting. c) Line size — 4\" may be undersized for restaurant volume. d) Grease trap condition — is it sized correctly? When was it last pumped? 3) PRESENT SOLUTIONS: a) Grease trap upgrade/installation — size per local code (typically 20-50 GPM for commercial kitchen). Weld County Health Department requires grease interceptors for food service. b) Biological grease treatment — enzyme-based product (BioOne or similar) injected monthly breaks down grease organically. c) Maintenance contract — monthly or quarterly jetting on schedule BEFORE blockages occur. d) Pipe replacement — if the line is old cast iron with heavy internal corrosion, grease adheres to the rough surface. A PVC reline or replacement gives a smooth surface that resists grease adhesion. 4) PRESENT THE MATH: '3 emergency calls at $595 each = $1,785/year in reactive work. A maintenance contract at $200/month = $2,400/year but includes guaranteed uptime — no more backed-up sewage during dinner rush. The maintenance plan is actually cheaper than the emergencies when you factor in lost revenue from closing during backups.'"},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the physics of how a hydro jetter cleans pipe compared to a cable machine, and why jetting produces superior long-term results.",a:"Cable machine: A rotating steel cable with a cutting head physically contacts the blockage and breaks it apart through mechanical force. The cutting head creates a CHANNEL through the blockage roug..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're running a cable through a main line and you hear a 'pop' followed by water spraying. You've punctured the pipe. What's the protocol?",a:"Pipe puncture during cable operation = immediate situation management: 1) STOP THE MACHINE. Do not advance or retract the cable. 2) ASSESS THE LOCATION: Where are you in the line? Inside the home? ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer has a septic system instead of city sewer. How does drain cleaning differ, and what additional precautions and sales opportunities apply?",a:"Septic system differences: 1) NEVER hydro-jet INTO the septic tank — high-pressure water stirs up the sludge layer and forces solids into the drain field, potentially destroying it ($20,000-40,000 ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Compare cast iron, clay, PVC, ABS, and orangeburg sewer pipe. How does pipe material affect your drain cleaning approach and what do you tell the customer about each?",a:"CAST IRON (1920s-1970s): Thick, durable when new, but Greeley's soil chemistry causes external corrosion and internal tuberculation (rust nodules). Cable: use carefully — aggressive heads can punch..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're running a cable machine and the cable suddenly gets stuck and won't advance or retract. What happened and what's the recovery procedure?",a:"A stuck cable is one of the most stressful situations in drain work. Causes: 1) CABLE KINKED IN A FITTING — the cable hit a sharp fitting (like a sanitary tee entered from the wrong direction) and ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between a sectional cable machine, a drum machine, and a water jetter. Which situations require which equipment?",a:"SECTIONAL MACHINE (Ridgid K-7500, Spartan): Cable sections (7.5 or 15 feet each) are added as needed. The cable is NOT enclosed in a drum — it's managed by hand as it enters the pipe. Advantages: l..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A restaurant owner calls with a grease-blocked kitchen drain line. This is the third time in 6 months. How do you solve this permanently?",a:"Recurring grease blockages indicate a systemic problem, not just a maintenance issue. Comprehensive solution: 1) CAMERA INSPECTION after clearing — document the pipe condition, diameter, slope, and..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're performing a camera inspection after a drain clearing and discover the customer has orangeburg pipe. Explain what this means and the recommended approach.",a:"Orangeburg pipe (bituminous fiber pipe) was used from the 1940s-1970s. It's made of layers of wood pulp and tar — essentially compressed felt paper soaked in coal tar pitch. Problems: 1) It deforms..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What are the different types of jetter nozzles and when do you use each one?",a:"Jetter nozzles are specialized for different blockage types: 1) PENETRATOR NOZZLE — forward-facing jets punch through blockages. Use for: initial breakthrough of grease or soft blockages. Not for r..."}
      ]},
    {id:20,name:"Toilet Repair & Replacement",category:"Plumbing",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"A customer says their toilet 'runs constantly.' Walk through the diagnosis step by step.",a:"1) Lift the tank lid and observe. Is water running into the overflow tube? If yes — fill valve is the problem (not shutting off). 2) If water level is below the overflow, add food coloring to the t..."},
        {q:"When should you recommend a full toilet replacement vs. internal repair?",a:"Recommend REPLACEMENT when: 1) The toilet is pre-1994 (uses 3.5-5 gallons per flush vs. modern 1.28-1.6 GPF — save the customer $100+/year on water). 2) The bowl is cracked — even hairline cracks c..."},
        {q:"Describe the correct procedure for installing a toilet on a flange that's too low (below the floor).",a:"A flange that's below the finished floor is the #1 cause of wax ring failures and toilet leaks. Options from best to worst: 1) BEST: Install a flange extender/spacer — raises the flange to floor le... below the floor, a spacer is required — wax alone won't bridge the gap reliably. Also check if the flange is broken — if the bolt slots are cracked, install a flange repair ring BEFORE setting the toilet. A loose toilet rocks, breaks the seal, and leaks sewage — one of the worst callbacks in residential plumbing."},
        {q:"A customer's toilet has a slow, weak flush. The tank is full and the water level is correct. What's the problem?",a:"Weak flush with full tank points to: 1) Clogged rim jets — mineral deposits (very common in Greeley hard water) block the small holes under the rim. Test: hold a mirror under the rim, flush, and lo..."},
        {q:"What are the most common mistakes technicians make during toilet installation?",a:"1) Not checking the flange height before setting — leads to immediate wax ring failure. Check and correct FIRST. 2) Over-tightening the closet bolts — cracks the porcelain base. Alternate sides, sn..."},
        {q:"A customer asks about bidet seats or smart toilets. How do you position this as an upsell?",a:"'That's actually one of the most popular upgrades we install. A bidet seat adds to your existing toilet — it needs a nearby electrical outlet (GFCI protected) and connects to your existing water su..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A toilet rocks on the floor and the customer notices a foul smell. Diagnose every possible cause and the correct repair sequence.",a:"Rocking toilet + sewer smell = compromised seal between toilet and waste pipe. Possible causes (check in order): 1) LOOSE CLOSET BOLTS: The bolts connecting the toilet to the flange have loosened. ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the internal hydraulics of a toilet flush — the siphon mechanism — and why this matters for diagnosing incomplete or phantom flushes.",a:"The toilet flush is a siphon, not a simple drain. Mechanics: When you flush, the flapper releases 1.6 gallons (modern) into the bowl rapidly. This surge raises the water level in the bowl above the..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's ADA/comfort-height toilet clogs frequently despite proper use. No flushable wipes, reasonable paper usage. What's the engineering explanation and the fix?",a:"Comfort-height (17-19\" seat height) toilets have a known engineering trade-off: the taller bowl requires a LONGER trapway to reach the waste pipe (which enters the floor at a fixed height). A longer trapway means: 1) More friction along the internal passage = weaker siphon force. 2) More surface area for waste to contact = higher clog probability. 3) The vertical drop from the bowl to the floor outlet may be steeper, but the horizontal section of the trap is longer. Additionally, low-flow toilets (1.28 GPF vs. older 3.5 GPF) provide less water energy to push waste through this longer path. The combination of comfort height + low flow = frequent clogs on certain models. Diagnosis: 1) Verify the toilet model — some manufacturers have known clogging issues (check MaP testing scores — Maximum Performance testing rates toilets on grams of waste per flush. Target: 600g+ MaP score). 2) Check the drain line downstream — a partial blockage or insufficient slope amplifies the problem. 3) Check the vent — an unvented or blocked vent reduces siphon strength. Fix options: 1) Replace with a higher MaP-scored model (Toto Drake, American Standard Champion — both score 1,000g). 2) If drain line is partially blocked, clear and camera it. 3) If vent is blocked, clear it. Present: 'Your toilet is a 400-gram model trying to do a 600-gram job. A toilet upgrade to a [brand] with a 4-inch trapway and 1,000-gram flush rating eliminates this problem permanently.'"},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're replacing a toilet and the cast iron closet flange is flush with the concrete slab but corroded. The bolt slots are intact but the flange ring is rough and pitted. Can you set a toilet on it, or must it be replaced?",a:"Corroded but functional flange = a judgment call with long-term implications. Assessment: 1) Are the bolt slots intact and holding? Test by inserting bolts and torquing — if they hold firm, the str..., the wax won't seal reliably. 3) Is the flange cracked? Corroded cast iron becomes brittle — tap it with a wrench. If it sounds solid, it's usable. If it sounds hollow or pieces flake off, it's done. Options: a) USABLE (pitting <1/8\", bolts hold, ring intact): Clean the surface with a wire brush, set a JUMBO wax ring (extra wax compensates for surface irregularities), or use a wax-free gasket (Danco Perfect Seal or Fernco) — wax-free seals are more forgiving on imperfect flanges. b) MARGINAL: Install a stainless steel repair ring ON TOP of the existing flange. This gives you fresh bolt slots and a new flat surface. Screws into the surrounding concrete with Tapcon anchors. c) MUST REPLACE: If the flange is broken, severely pitted, or pulling away from the pipe. For cast iron on concrete, this means cutting the existing flange and installing a PVC replacement using a Fernco coupling or mission band. This adds 1-2 hours to the job. Always present the customer with findings: 'Your flange is corroded. I can set your new toilet with a heavy-duty seal for $X, or I can replace the flange for $Y which gives you a brand-new foundation. I recommend the flange replacement because it guarantees a perfect seal for 20+ years.'"},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the water savings and cost payback for a customer replacing two 3.5 GPF toilets from 1990 with two 1.28 GPF WaterSense toilets.",a:"Calculation: Average flushes per person per day: 5. Household of 4: 20 flushes/day. OLD: 20 × 3.5 = 70 gallons/day on toilets. NEW: 20 × 1.28 = 25.6 gallons/day on toilets. SAVINGS: 44.4 gallons/da..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's toilet rocks on the floor even after tightening the closet bolts. The flange appears to be at floor level. What's the complete diagnostic and repair process?",a:"Rocking toilet with a level flange indicates an uneven floor or flange issue. Diagnostic: 1) Remove the toilet completely. 2) Inspect the flange: is it cracked? Are the bolt slots intact? Is it lev... of unevenness causes rocking that eventually breaks the wax seal. 4) Check for rot: water damage around the flange weakens the subfloor. Push a screwdriver into the subfloor around the flange — soft wood means rot. Repair process by severity: MINOR UNEVENNESS: Set the toilet, find the gap points, insert plastic toilet shims (not wood — wood absorbs water). Once stable, caulk the base to lock shims in place and prevent debris/water intrusion. Leave a 1\" gap at the back for leak detection. CRACKED FLANGE: Install a flange repair ring (stainless steel) over the existing flange. Secure with new screws into solid subfloor — NOT into the original screw holes. ROTTED SUBFLOOR: Cut out the damaged section, sister new wood to the existing joists, install new subfloor (3/4\" plywood minimum), install a new flange at proper height. This escalates a $200 job to an $800-1,200 job — show the customer the damage and explain why it must be done right: 'Sewer gas leaking under your floor is a health hazard, and the water damage will spread to the surrounding area. Let me fix this properly so it lasts.'"},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the hydraulics of a toilet flush — what happens from handle press to bowl refill — and how understanding this helps diagnose problems.",a:"Phase 1 — FLUSH ACTIVATION: Handle lifts the flapper via chain. Water rushes from tank into bowl through the flush valve opening (2\" standard, 3\" on performance toilets). Phase 2 — SIPHON CREATION: Water entering the bowl raises the water level above the internal trapway weir point. Once water crests the trap, gravity creates a siphon — atmospheric pressure pushes water over the trap. This is the 'whoosh' sound. The bowl empties rapidly. Phase 3 — SIPHON BREAK: When the tank is nearly empty, air enters through the flush valve or jet hole, breaking the siphon. You hear the gurgle. Phase 4 — REFILL: The flapper closes. The fill valve opens, sending water through two paths simultaneously: directly into the tank (through the tank fill tube) AND into the bowl (through the refill tube connected to the overflow pipe). The bowl refills to maintain the water seal in the trap. The tank fills until the float reaches the set level and shuts off the fill valve. DIAGNOSTIC APPLICATIONS: Weak flush = insufficient water volume entering bowl (low tank level, partially closed flapper, clogged rim jets reducing siphon formation). Ghost flush = slow flapper leak drains tank, fill valve activates periodically. Incomplete flush = trapway partially blocked, preventing full siphon. Slow bowl refill = kinked or disconnected refill tube (water goes to tank only, not bowl). Bowl water level drops between flushes = cracked bowl, bad wax seal venting the trap, or vent pipe blockage causing trap siphonage."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer has a toilet that backs up only when the washing machine drains. Other fixtures are fine. What's the diagnostic path?",a:"This is a VENTING problem, not a drain blockage. When the washing machine dumps 15-20 gallons rapidly, it creates a surge in the shared drain line. If the vent serving the toilet is blocked or inad... branch serving both the toilet and washing machine may be undersized for simultaneous flow. Code requires 3\" minimum when a toilet is on the branch. 4) Check for a missing or disconnected vent. 5) Test: run the washer on drain cycle while monitoring the toilet. If the toilet gurgles and bubbles, it's definitively a vent issue. Fix: clear the vent blockage. If the vent is undersized, add a supplemental vent or install an AAV at the laundry drain."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the difference between a gravity-flush, pressure-assist, and vacuum-assist toilet? When would you recommend each?",a:"GRAVITY-FLUSH: Water falls from tank into bowl by gravity alone. The weight and volume of water create the siphon. 1.28-1.6 GPF. Quietest operation. Most common residential toilet. Works well for t... flush valve and large trapway (2-1/8\" minimum). Brands like Toto Drake and Kohler Highline consistently score highest in flush performance tests."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer wants to convert from a floor-mount toilet to a wall-hung toilet during a bathroom remodel. What are the structural and plumbing requirements?",a:"Wall-hung toilets require significant structural and plumbing modifications: STRUCTURAL: 1) A steel carrier frame must be installed inside the wall — this frame supports the toilet AND the user's w... wide × 36\" tall for the carrier. 3) Standard 2×4 walls may need to be converted to 2×6 or a furred-out cavity to accommodate the carrier depth (typically 8-9\" deep). PLUMBING: 1) The drain connection changes from FLOOR (12\" rough-in) to WALL (typically 8-10\" above finished floor). The drain must be rerouted through the wall cavity to the stack. 2) Supply line reroutes to the concealed tank (in-wall tank). 3) The concealed tank and flush mechanism are built into the carrier — all serviceable through the flush plate opening. 4) A separate access panel is recommended for the fill valve and flush valve in case of future service. CODE: Verify with Weld County that wall-hung toilets are approved for the specific installation. The carrier must meet ASME A112.6.1M standards. COST: The carrier alone is $500-800. Combined with the toilet ($400-1,200), wall modification, plumbing reroute, tile work, and labor, total cost is $3,500-6,000. Present: 'Wall-hung toilets look amazing and make floor cleaning much easier. The install is more involved than a standard toilet because we need to install a structural frame and reroute the drain through the wall. Here are your three options...'"}
      ]},
    {id:21,name:"Faucet & Fixture Service",category:"Plumbing",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"A customer has a dripping kitchen faucet. What's your diagnostic approach?",a:"1) Identify the faucet type — this determines the repair method: Single-handle cartridge (Moen, Delta, Kohler), single-handle ball (Delta), compression (two handles, older style), or ceramic disc (..."},
        {q:"When should you recommend repair vs. replacement for a faucet?",a:"Recommend REPLACEMENT when: 1) The faucet is 15+ years old — parts availability decreases and finish deterioration makes it look worn. 2) The repair cost exceeds 40% of a new faucet install — commo..."},
        {q:"A customer's kitchen faucet has low water pressure but other fixtures are fine. What are the top causes?",a:"1) Clogged aerator — unscrew the aerator from the spout, check for mineral buildup or debris. This fixes 50% of single-fixture low pressure complaints. Clean with vinegar or replace. 2) Clogged car..."},
        {q:"You're installing a new kitchen faucet and the old shut-off valves are corroded gate valves that barely turn. What do you do?",a:"This is one of the most important upsells in residential plumbing. ALWAYS recommend replacing old gate valves with 1/4-turn ball valves during any faucet install. Script: 'I want to show you someth..."},
        {q:"What are the top 5 faucet cartridge types you should always have in your truck stock?",a:"1) Moen 1222 — single-handle Moen shower/tub valves. The most common residential shower cartridge in America. 2) Moen 1225 — single-handle Moen kitchen and lav faucets. 3) Delta RP46074 — Delta Mon..."},
        {q:"A customer asks you to install a faucet they bought from Amazon. What's the JT Plumbing policy and how do you handle it?",a:"JT Plumbing installs customer-supplied fixtures with clear communication: 'Absolutely — I can install that for you. I just want to make sure you know two things upfront: 1) Our warranty covers the ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're replacing an old 3-handle tub/shower valve with a single-handle pressure-balancing valve. Walk through the complete procedure and code requirements.",a:"This is a permit-required rough-in modification. Procedure: 1) Shut off water to the house, drain the lines. 2) Open the wall (either from the front through tile — destructive, or from an access pa... from the tub floor (handle height). 5) Connect hot to LEFT, cold to RIGHT (universal code requirement — hot on left). 6) Solder or use PEX connections depending on existing piping. 7) Install new trim kit and handle on the wall side. 8) If going through tile: coordinate with a tile contractor for the wall patch, OR install a large-format escutcheon plate to cover the old valve holes. Code requirements: Colorado UPC requires pressure-balancing or thermostatic mixing valves in ALL new tub/shower installations. Max outlet temp: 120°F. Anti-scald protection is non-negotiable — if the cold water pressure drops (someone flushes a toilet), the valve must reduce hot water proportionally to prevent scalding. Pull permit, schedule inspection. This is a $1,500-2,500 job that homeowners love because it modernizes a dated bathroom."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer has a touchless kitchen faucet that activates randomly — turning on by itself. Diagnose the electronic and plumbing causes.",a:"Touchless faucets use infrared (IR) sensors to detect hand presence. Random activation causes: 1) SENSOR SENSITIVITY TOO HIGH: Most touchless faucets have an adjustable sensitivity setting (accessi..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between ceramic disc, cartridge, ball, and compression faucet mechanisms. How does each fail and what determines repair vs. replace?",a:"COMPRESSION (oldest design): Two handles, each with a rubber washer that compresses against a brass seat. Fails: washers wear out (drip), seats corrode (drip continues after washer replacement). Re..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer complains of low hot water pressure at ALL fixtures but cold pressure is fine. The water heater is 8 years old. What's the systematic diagnosis?",a:"Low hot pressure everywhere with normal cold = the restriction is somewhere in the hot water distribution system between the water heater outlet and the fixtures. Systematic: 1) WATER HEATER DIP TU..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer has a single-handle shower valve and gets scalded when someone flushes a toilet. Explain why this happens and the code-required solution.",a:"Physics: When a toilet flushes, it draws 1.28-1.6 gallons from the cold water supply in about 10 seconds. This creates a sudden DROP in cold water pressure at the shower valve. If the shower valve ..."}
      ]},
    {id:22,name:"Water Line Repair & Repipe",category:"Plumbing",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"A customer has a slab leak. How do you identify the location and present the repair options?",a:"Detection: 1) Listen for running water with everything off. 2) Check the water meter — if the dial spins with all fixtures off, there's a leak. 3) Use electronic leak detection equipment — amplifie..."},
        {q:"What is PEX and why does JT Plumbing recommend it for repipes over copper?",a:"PEX (cross-linked polyethylene) advantages: 1) Flexible — fewer connections means fewer potential leak points. Can bend around corners without fittings. 2) Freeze-resistant — PEX expands without bu..."},
        {q:"A customer calls about discolored water — brown/rust-colored. What's the diagnostic process?",a:"1) Run COLD water only for 2 minutes. If it clears, the issue is in the home's piping (internal corrosion). If it doesn't clear, it may be the city main — check with a neighbor. 2) Run HOT water on..."},
        {q:"How do you present a whole-home repipe to a customer who wasn't expecting that kind of expense?",a:"Empathy first: 'I know a repipe isn't what you called us for today, and I completely understand the sticker shock. Let me explain why I'm recommending it and then show you some options that might w..."},
        {q:"What are the critical steps when working on the main water service line coming into the home?",a:"1) Locate the main shut-off — at the meter, NOT the house valve (house valves often don't fully close). 2) Call the utility if you need the meter shut off or if you're working near the meter. In Gr..."},
        {q:"A pipe bursts in a finished basement ceiling at 11 PM. Walk through the emergency response protocol.",a:"Phone protocol: 'I understand this is stressful — let's get through this together. First, have you been able to shut off the water? There should be a main shut-off valve near where the water line e..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the galvanic corrosion process in a home with mixed copper and galvanized steel piping. Why do these connections fail and what's the code-compliant solution?",a:"Galvanic corrosion occurs when two dissimilar metals are connected in the presence of an electrolyte (water). The galvanic series ranks metals by their electrochemical potential. Copper is more 'no..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's home was built in 1965 and has lead solder joints on the copper water supply lines. What's the health risk, testing protocol, and remediation approach?",a:"Lead solder was common until the Safe Drinking Water Act amendments of 1986 banned it. Pre-1986 homes may have 50/50 tin-lead solder (50% lead) at every joint. Health risk: lead leaches into standi..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You're performing a whole-home PEX repipe using a manifold system. Explain the design advantages of manifold vs. trunk-and-branch, and the installation procedure.",a:"TRUNK-AND-BRANCH (traditional): One main hot line and one main cold line run through the house, with branches teeing off to individual fixtures. Pros: less tubing, familiar to most plumbers. Cons: ... PEX lines to lavatories and 1/2\" PEX to showers, tubs, and kitchen. 3) Use PEX-A with Uponor expansion fittings (strongest, most reliable connection). 4) Support tubing every 32\" on horizontal runs, 48\" on vertical. 5) Keep hot and cold lines 6\" apart minimum. 6) Insulate hot water lines in unconditioned spaces. 7) Label every line at the manifold (Kitchen Hot, Master Bath Cold, etc.). 8) Pressure test entire system at 80 PSI for 30 minutes before closing walls."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer calls — their water bill tripled last month but they see no visible leaks. Walk through the systematic leak detection process for hidden and underground leaks.",a:"Hidden leak detection process: 1) METER TEST: Turn off all water-using appliances and fixtures. Read the water meter. Wait 30 minutes with no water use. Read again. If the meter moved, you have a l..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the freeze protection considerations for water lines in Northern Colorado construction. What are the code requirements, common failure points, and prevention strategies?",a:"Colorado frost line: 42\" minimum burial depth (Weld County). This means the main water service line must be buried 42\" or deeper. Common failure points: 1) SERVICE LINE ENTRY: Where the water line comes through the foundation wall — if the entry is above the frost line or poorly insulated, this section freezes first. The pipe is cold from underground but exposed to basement air that may be below freezing near the rim joist. 2) EXTERIOR HOSE BIBS: Frost-free sillcocks are code-required in new construction but older homes have traditional bibs that freeze. 3) PIPES IN EXTERIOR WALLS: Kitchen sinks on exterior walls, bathroom supply lines in outside walls — common in 1960s-1980s construction. 4) CRAWLSPACE PIPES: Uninsulated crawlspaces expose water lines to below-freezing air. 5) GARAGE PIPES: Water heaters and laundry in unheated garages. Prevention strategies: a) INSULATION: Minimum R-4 foam pipe insulation on all water lines in unconditioned spaces. R-8 for high-risk areas. b) HEAT TRACE CABLE: Electric heating cable wrapped around pipes in high-risk areas. Self-regulating type adjusts heat output based on temperature. Critical for service line entry points and crawlspaces. c) FROST-FREE SILLCOCKS: Replace all traditional exterior bibs with 8\" or 12\" frost-free sillcocks (the valve seat is inside the heated envelope of the house). d) CABINET DOORS: Advise customers to open cabinet doors under sinks on exterior walls during cold snaps (allows warm room air to circulate around pipes). e) DRIP FAUCETS: A slight drip prevents freezing by maintaining flow. Sales opportunity: 'Every January we get 20+ burst pipe calls. A $500 freeze protection package — insulation, heat cable, and frost-free bibs — prevents a $3,000-10,000 water damage disaster. It's the cheapest insurance in plumbing.'"},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the PEX-A expansion fitting system vs. PEX-B crimp rings vs. PEX-B clamp rings. Why does JT Plumbing use PEX-A?",a:"PEX-A (Expansion method, Uponor): The pipe is expanded with an expansion tool, the PPSU (polyphenylsulfone) fitting is inserted, and the pipe contracts back to its original size around the fitting ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer on a well system has fluctuating water pressure — strong, then weak, then surging. Diagnose the well system issues.",a:"Fluctuating pressure on a well system is a pressure tank or pump problem. Diagnostic approach: 1) CHECK THE PRESSURE TANK: Press the Schrader valve (like a tire valve) on the tank. If WATER comes o..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What are the health implications of different pipe materials found in older homes, and how do you advise customers?",a:"LEAD PIPE (pre-1950): Found as service lines from the main to the house and occasionally as interior supply lines. Lead leaches into standing water, especially soft/acidic water. Health impact: neu..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Describe the procedure for performing a whole-home manifold PEX repipe, including the manifold system design.",a:"Manifold design (home-run system): Every fixture gets its own dedicated PEX line from a central manifold — similar to an electrical breaker panel for water. Components: 1) MANIFOLD LOCATION: Instal... main feed to the manifold. 1/2\" PEX home-runs to most fixtures. 3/8\" PEX can serve lavatories. 3/4\" for bathtubs with high-flow requirements. 4) ROUTING: Run PEX through floor cavities, ceiling joists, or attic space. Each line runs directly from the manifold to its fixture — no tees, no branches, no connections inside walls. 5) LABELING: Label every port at the manifold with its destination fixture. 6) SHUT-OFF VALVES: Each port has its own shut-off — the homeowner can isolate any fixture without affecting the rest of the house. This is the #1 selling point. 7) TESTING: Pressure test the entire system at 80 PSI for 2 hours before closing walls. Advantages: individual fixture control, fewer potential leak points (connections only at manifold and fixture), balanced pressure across all fixtures, faster installation (no fittings inside walls). Present: 'Think of this like upgrading from old fuse box to a modern breaker panel — individual control over every water line in your house, no hidden connections in your walls, and balanced pressure everywhere.'"}
      ]},
    {id:23,name:"Garbage Disposal & Sump Pump",category:"Plumbing",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"A customer's garbage disposal hums but doesn't spin. Walk through the diagnosis.",a:"1) SAFETY FIRST — turn off the wall switch. Verify power is off. Never put your hand in a disposal. 2) Check for a jam: use the Allen wrench (1/4\" hex) in the bottom center of the unit. Turn it back and forth to free the flywheel. 3) If it frees and spins manually, press the reset button on the bottom of the unit. Turn on and test. 4) If the flywheel won't budge, the jam is severe — try from the top with a disposal wrench or wooden broom handle. 5) If it spins freely but still just hums — the motor capacitor or motor itself is failing. At this point, it's replacement time. 6) Check the unit's age — disposals last 8-12 years. If it's over 8 and has issues, recommend replacement. 'I can try to free this up for $X, but your disposal is 10 years old and once they start jamming, it's a pattern. For $Y I can install a new one today with a 5-year warranty. Which would you prefer?'"},
        {q:"What's the correct installation procedure for a garbage disposal?",a:"1) Turn off power at the breaker — lockout/tagout. 2) Disconnect and remove the old unit (support it from below while removing the mounting ring — they're heavy). 3) If reusing the existing mountin..."},
        {q:"A customer's sump pump isn't running and the pit is filling up. What's the emergency protocol?",a:"1) Check power — is it plugged in? Is the outlet working? (Plug something else in to verify.) 2) Check the float switch — manually lift it. Does the pump activate? If not, it's a pump motor failure..."},
        {q:"What sump pump system do you recommend for Northern Colorado homes and why?",a:"Good ($800-1,200): 1/3 HP primary pump with cast iron housing, mechanical float switch. Gets the job done for normal water tables. Better ($1,500-2,200): 1/2 HP primary pump with electronic float s..."},
        {q:"What maintenance should be performed on a sump pump and how often?",a:"Quarterly: 1) Pour 5 gallons of water into the pit — verify the pump activates and the float switch works. 2) Check the discharge line — ensure it's not disconnected, frozen, or blocked. 3) Clean t..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A sump pump runs every 3-5 minutes even when it hasn't rained. The discharge line is clear. What are the possible causes and how do you diagnose each?",a:"Frequent cycling without rain = continuous water infiltration into the pit. Causes: 1) HIGH WATER TABLE: In east Greeley and Evans, the water table can be within 4-6 feet of surface. Groundwater se..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's garbage disposal is tripping the GFCI outlet repeatedly. The disposal runs fine for 5-10 seconds, then the GFCI trips. Diagnose the electrical and mechanical causes.",a:"GFCI trips when current leakage to ground exceeds 5 milliamps. The disposal works briefly because the motor initially draws within limits, then something causes a ground fault. Causes: 1) MOISTURE ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the proper sizing calculation for a sump pump in a home with high water table conditions in eastern Weld County.",a:"Sump pump sizing is based on INFLOW RATE to the pit, not the pit size or the home size. Measurement method: 1) Let the pit fill to the pump's activation level. 2) Pump the pit dry and note the time... × 24\" × 18\" deep water level = 2.8 cubic feet = 21 gallons. Refill time: 8 minutes. Inflow: 21/8 = 2.6 GPM. If TDH is 12 feet (8 feet vertical + friction): A 1/3 HP pump delivers approximately 2,500 GPH (42 GPM) at 12 feet TDH. At 2.6 GPM inflow, the 1/3 HP pump runs about 4% of the time — adequate with huge margin. BUT: for high water table in east Greeley during spring melt, inflow can spike to 15-20 GPM. At that rate, a 1/3 HP pump runs 35-48% duty cycle. Upgrade to 1/2 HP for margin and longevity — motors that run near capacity overheat and fail faster. ALWAYS install battery backup for high-water-table homes. When the power goes out during a spring thunderstorm, that 15 GPM fills a basement in 2-3 hours."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer wants a new garbage disposal and asks about the difference between 1/3 HP, 1/2 HP, 3/4 HP, and 1 HP models. What do you recommend and why?",a:"HP differences — it's about TORQUE, not just power: 1/3 HP: Budget tier. Handles light use — soft foods, small quantities. Jams easily on fibrous foods (celery, potato skins). Recovery from jams is..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's sump pump runs constantly even during dry weather. The pit fills rapidly. What's the advanced diagnosis?",a:"Constant running in dry conditions indicates a water source that isn't seasonal surface water. Investigate: 1) HIGH WATER TABLE — the natural water table in the area may be at or above the sump pit..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the difference between a sump pump, an ejector pump, and a sewage grinder pump. When is each required?",a:"SUMP PUMP: Handles CLEAN or gray water — groundwater, condensate, washing machine overflow, floor drain water. Pumps to the exterior away from the foundation. NO solid waste capability. Typical 1/3... solids. Installed in a sealed, vented basin. 2\" discharge line connects to the building's main sewer above the flood level. Typically 1/2 to 1 HP. Must have a check valve and gate valve on the discharge. The basin must be GAS-TIGHT with a sealed lid — sewer gas ventilation is through the vent pipe, not the lid. SEWAGE GRINDER PUMP: Similar to an ejector but with a grinding mechanism that reduces solids to slurry. Used when the discharge line must be small diameter (1-1/4\" to 2\") over long distances or when pumping vertically 20+ feet. Higher HP (3/4 to 2 HP). More expensive and more maintenance. Critical distinction for code: If a customer wants to add a basement bathroom, you MUST install a sewage ejector system — you cannot connect toilet, shower, and sink drains to a sump pump. The permit will require an ejector pump with a properly sized, sealed, and vented basin. Price difference: sump pump replacement $800-1,500 vs. ejector pump system installation $3,500-6,000."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A basement bathroom ejector pump is emitting sewer gas into the basement. The pump works fine otherwise. Diagnose and fix.",a:"Sewer gas from an ejector system means the sealed system has been compromised. Diagnostic: 1) LID SEAL — the ejector basin lid must be gas-tight. Check: is the lid properly seated with a rubber gas..."}
      ]},
    {id:24,name:"Water Softener & Filtration",category:"Plumbing",required:false,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"Greeley has some of the hardest water in Colorado. What are the hardness levels and why does it matter?",a:"Greeley/Evans water runs 15-25 grains per gallon (GPG) — extremely hard. Windsor and surrounding areas can reach 30+ GPG. For reference: 0-3 GPG is soft, 7-10 is hard, 15+ is very hard. Hard water ..."},
        {q:"Walk through a water softener installation for a typical Greeley home.",a:"1) Choose the location — typically near the water main entry, before the water heater, in the garage or utility room. Need: floor drain or condensate line nearby, electrical outlet, and a drain for..."},
        {q:"A customer asks 'Do I really need a water softener? My water seems fine.' How do you respond?",a:"Don't argue — demonstrate. 'Let me show you something.' Then: 1) Pull out a water hardness test strip — test their tap water right there. Show the result: 'See this? Your water is 22 grains hard. T..."},
        {q:"What's the difference between a water softener and a whole-home water filtration system?",a:"Water softener: Removes hardness minerals (calcium, magnesium) using ion exchange resin. Replaces calcium/magnesium with sodium. Prevents scale, improves soap lather, protects pipes and appliances...."},
        {q:"A customer already has a water softener that's 12 years old and no longer softening. Diagnose and present options.",a:"Diagnostic steps: 1) Check the salt level — is the brine tank empty or bridged (a hard salt crust on top with space underneath)? Break the bridge with a broom handle. 2) Check the resin — pull a sa..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the ion exchange process in a water softener at the molecular level. How does regeneration restore capacity, and why does salt consumption vary?",a:"Ion exchange: The resin tank contains thousands of small polystyrene beads coated with sodium ions (Na+). Hard water contains calcium (Ca²+) and magnesium (Mg²+) ions. As water flows through the re..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's softened water has a 'slippery' feeling and they don't like it. They ask if the softener is adding something harmful. How do you address their concern with science?",a:"The 'slippery' feeling is the #1 complaint from new softener owners. Explain the science: 'The slippery feeling isn't something we added — it's something we removed. Hard water leaves a film of cal..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Compare salt-based softeners, salt-free conditioners, and reverse osmosis systems. When does each apply, and what are the honest limitations?",a:"SALT-BASED SOFTENER: True water softening — removes calcium and magnesium via ion exchange. RESULTS: eliminates scale, extends appliance life, soap lathers fully, skin and hair feel softer. LIMITAT..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: You install a new water softener and the customer calls back 3 days later saying their water heater is leaking from the T&P valve since the softener went in. Is this related?",a:"YES — this is a direct consequence of the softener installation, and it's a known phenomenon. Explanation: Soft water is more aggressive to mineral deposits than hard water. The existing water heat..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the ion exchange process in a water softener at a chemistry level. Why does resin need to regenerate?",a:"Ion exchange chemistry: The softener tank contains thousands of tiny resin beads made of polystyrene crosslinked with divinylbenzene. These beads carry a NEGATIVE charge. During manufacturing, they..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's water softener is using excessive salt — going through 80 lbs per month when it should use 40 lbs. Diagnose the problem.",a:"Excessive salt consumption means the system is regenerating too frequently or using too much brine per regeneration. Diagnostic: 1) CHECK REGENERATION FREQUENCY — how often does it regenerate? If i..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer asks about salt-free water conditioners vs. traditional softeners. Give an honest, technically accurate comparison.",a:"SALT-BASED SOFTENER (ion exchange): ACTUALLY REMOVES hardness minerals from the water. Output water is truly soft — 0-3 grains. Benefits: eliminates scale completely, soap lathers properly, skin/ha..."}
      ]},
    {id:25,name:"Boiler & Radiant Heat Basics",category:"HVAC",required:false,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"A customer's hot water baseboard system isn't heating. What's your diagnostic approach?",a:"1) Check the thermostat — is it calling for heat? Set above room temp. 2) Check the boiler — is it firing? Listen for the burner igniting. Check the display for error codes. 3) Check the circulator..."},
        {q:"What is the correct procedure for bleeding air from a hot water baseboard heating system?",a:"1) Turn off the system and let it cool slightly. 2) Locate the bleed valves — small screws/valves on top of each baseboard unit or radiator, typically at the highest point. 3) Start at the HIGHEST ..."},
        {q:"When should you recommend a boiler replacement vs. repair?",a:"Replace when: 1) The boiler is 25+ years old (boilers last 20-35 years, but efficiency drops significantly after 20). 2) The heat exchanger has cracks or leaks — not cost-effective to repair. 3) An..."},
        {q:"A customer asks about converting from baseboard heat to a forced-air furnace. What do you advise?",a:"This is a major decision. Walk through pros and cons: Keep baseboard/boiler: Pros — silent operation, even heat, no ductwork to install, zones already exist. Cons — no central AC capability (would ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's hydronic radiant floor heating system has cold spots in certain rooms. The boiler is running and the circulator pump is operating. Systematic diagnosis?",a:"Radiant floor cold spots with a running system: 1) AIRLOCK: Air trapped in the tubing loop prevents water circulation. This is the #1 cause of cold zones in radiant floor systems. Diagnosis: feel t..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain how a modulating/condensing boiler achieves 95%+ efficiency versus a standard 80% AFUE boiler. What are the critical maintenance differences?",a:"Standard (80% AFUE) boiler: Has a single-pass heat exchanger that extracts PRIMARY heat from combustion gases. Exhaust exits at 350-450°F — all that heat goes up the chimney. The water vapor in the..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer has radiant floor heat in the basement but wants to add baseboard heat to the second floor. Can the same boiler serve both? What are the design considerations?",a:"Yes — one boiler can serve both radiant floor and baseboard, but the design is complex because they operate at DIFFERENT temperatures. Radiant floor: Operates at 90-130°F water temperature. Higher ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A hot water boiler system has a consistently high pressure reading (above 25 PSI) even when cold. The expansion tank was just replaced. What else could cause this?",a:"If the expansion tank is new and properly sized, investigate: 1) EXPANSION TANK PRE-CHARGE — the air bladder must be pre-charged to match the system's COLD fill pressure (typically 12-15 PSI). If t..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the differences between a standard boiler, a condensing boiler, and a combi boiler. When do you recommend each?",a:"STANDARD BOILER (80-85% AFUE): Non-condensing. Return water temperature must stay above 140°F to prevent flue gas condensation (which creates acidic condensate that corrodes the heat exchanger). Be..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is an outdoor reset curve and why is it critical for condensing boiler efficiency?",a:"An outdoor reset controller adjusts the boiler water temperature based on outdoor air temperature. Concept: On a mild 45°F day, your home needs less heat than on a 0°F day. Without outdoor reset, t..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A radiant floor heating system has cold spots in certain zones. The manifold zone valves are opening correctly. What's the advanced diagnosis?",a:"With zone valves confirmed operational, investigate: 1) AIR LOCK IN THE LOOP — even small air bubbles in radiant tubing reduce circulation dramatically. Each zone must be individually purged throug..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's boiler relief valve is discharging water periodically. The expansion tank appears functional. Perform a systematic diagnosis.",a:"Relief valve discharge = system pressure exceeding the valve rating (typically 30 PSI for residential boilers). Systematic approach: 1) MONITOR PRESSURE OVER A FULL HEATING CYCLE — install a pressu..."}
      ]},
    {id:26,name:"Building the Review & Referral Machine",category:"Sales",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What is the JT Plumbing review generation protocol? When and how do you ask?",a:"WHEN to ask: Only after the customer expresses satisfaction. Listen for: 'Looks great,' 'Thank you so much,' 'You guys are awesome.' Never ask if they seem unhappy. HOW to ask (the 3-step method): ..."},
        {q:"What's the target review conversion rate and how do experts track their performance?",a:"Targets: Ask rate: 100% of satisfied customers (non-negotiable). Conversion rate: 40% of asks should result in a posted review. If you're asking 100% and converting 40%, that means roughly 1 review..."},
        {q:"A customer leaves a negative Google review. What's the response protocol?",a:"1) Don't panic. Don't respond emotionally. Wait 1 hour minimum before responding. 2) The owner or manager responds publicly — never the tech. 3) Use this template: 'Thank you for sharing your exper..."},
        {q:"How does the referral program work and what's the tech's role in generating referrals?",a:"Program: $50 gift card to the referring customer + $50 off for the new customer. Both sides win. Tech's role: Plant the seed at EVERY job: 'Hey, do you know anyone else in the neighborhood who migh..."},
        {q:"A customer gives you a 5-star review and mentions you by name. How do you leverage this?",a:"1) Thank them personally — text or call: 'I saw your review and it really made my day. Thank you for taking the time.' 2) Screenshot it and send it to the team group chat — recognition motivates ev..."},
        {q:"What's the difference between a Google review, a Yelp review, and a BBB review? Where should we focus?",a:"Priority order: 1) Google — 90% of our focus. Google reviews directly affect our Local Services Ads ranking, Google Maps position, and Search ranking. More Google reviews = more calls. 2) Facebook ..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Your Google Business Profile shows 4.6 stars with 180 reviews. A competitor has 4.8 stars with 65 reviews. Who ranks higher in Google Maps and why? What's the strategy to beat them?",a:"Google's local ranking algorithm considers three factors: RELEVANCE (how well the listing matches the search), DISTANCE (proximity to the searcher), and PROMINENCE (how well-known and trusted the b..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the lifetime value (LTV) of a single Google review. How much revenue does each review generate over time?",a:"This is the math that makes review generation a top priority: Direct conversion: Studies show a 1-star increase in Google rating leads to a 5-9% increase in revenue. For a company doing $1.5M/year,..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A competitor is suspected of buying fake Google reviews — they went from 30 reviews to 90 reviews in one month, all 5-star, all from accounts with no profile pictures and only one review. What do you do?",a:"Fake reviews violate Google's policies and potentially FTC regulations. Response: 1) DO NOT engage in fake reviews yourself — ever. It's a felony-level FTC violation since 2023 (up to $50,000 per f..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A loyal customer refers three friends, generating $12,000 in combined revenue. Describe the tiered appreciation strategy that turns this customer into a permanent referral engine.",a:"Referral appreciation should ESCALATE with volume — the more they refer, the more valued they feel: TIER 1 (1 referral): Standard referral reward — $50 gift card + handwritten thank-you card from t..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Create a monthly review response strategy. How should you handle 5-star, 4-star, 3-star, and 1-2 star reviews differently?",a:"5-STAR REVIEWS: Respond within 24 hours. Personalize — mention the tech by name and the service performed. 'Thank you [Name]! We're glad [Tech] was able to get your [service] taken care of quickly...."}
      ]},
    {id:27,name:"Ductwork & Airflow Diagnostics",category:"HVAC",required:false,techs:{1:false,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"A customer says one room in their house is always hot in summer and cold in winter. Diagnose the airflow problem.",a:"1) Check the obvious: is the register open? Is furniture blocking it? You'd be surprised — this fixes 20% of comfort complaints. 2) Measure supply air temperature at the problem register vs. a regi... WC total, it's fighting the ductwork. Solution: seal, insulate, or add a dedicated duct run to the problem room."},
        {q:"What are the signs of ductwork that needs repair or replacement?",a:"Visible signs: 1) Flex duct that's crushed, kinked, or hanging by a thread in the attic/crawlspace. 2) Visible gaps at connections — duct tape (ironically) fails after 1-2 years. Look for separated... WC total (high = restricted). 2) Temperature differential between rooms exceeds 3-4°F. 3) Energy bills are 20-30% higher than comparable homes. 4) The system runs constantly but can't reach setpoint. Rule of thumb: if ductwork is over 20 years old, it's likely 25-40% leaky. Sealing alone can improve efficiency 15-25%."},
        {q:"How do you explain duct sealing to a homeowner who doesn't understand why it matters?",a:"Analogy: 'Imagine you're watering your garden with a hose that has 10 holes in it. You turn the water on full blast, but your garden only gets half the water — the rest sprays into the air. That's ..."},
        {q:"A customer's furnace keeps tripping the high-limit switch. The filter is clean. What's the next airflow diagnostic step?",a:"If the filter is clean and the high-limit is still tripping, work through the airflow chain: 1) Check ALL return air paths — are any returns blocked by furniture, rugs, or closed doors? A house nee... WC on return side), the return ductwork is undersized. 6) Check for crushed ductwork — climb in the attic or crawlspace and physically inspect every run. A crushed flex duct in the attic is invisible from inside the house."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain static pressure measurement in HVAC ductwork. What are acceptable readings and what do they tell you?",a:"Static pressure is the resistance to airflow in the duct system — think of it as the 'blood pressure' of your HVAC system. Measurement: Use a digital manometer with static pressure tips. Drill a 3/8\" test hole in the supply plenum (after the coil) and return plenum (before the filter). TOTAL EXTERNAL STATIC PRESSURE = supply reading + return reading. Acceptable: Most residential furnaces are designed for 0.50\" WC total external static pressure. Readings by location: RETURN SIDE: Should be -0.10\" to -0.20\" WC. Higher than -0.25\" = restricted return (undersized ductwork, dirty filter, blocked return grilles). SUPPLY SIDE: Should be +0.20\" to +0.30\" WC. Higher than +0.35\" = restricted supply (undersized ductwork, dirty coil, closed dampers). TOTAL over 0.50\" WC: The blower is working harder than designed. Consequences: reduced airflow by 15-30%, increased energy consumption, premature blower motor failure, comfort complaints, and limit switch trips. TOTAL over 0.80\" WC: Severe restriction. Immediate attention required. This single measurement tells you more about system performance than almost any other diagnostic. Every furnace call should include a static pressure reading."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer wants to add an HVAC zone to their existing single-zone system. What are the engineering considerations?",a:"Adding zones to an existing system requires careful engineering: 1) STATIC PRESSURE IMPACT — when one zone closes, the remaining open zones must absorb the full system airflow. This creates high st..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: How do you perform a Manual D duct design for a residential system? What are the consequences of skipping this step?",a:"Manual D is the ACCA-standard procedure for sizing ductwork. Steps: 1) Start with the Manual J load calculation — this gives you the TOTAL CFM required (typically 400 CFM per ton of cooling). 2) Ca... WC per 100 feet for residential) divided by the equivalent length of each run determines the friction rate. 5) Using a ductulator or ACCA tables, select the duct size that delivers the required CFM at the available friction rate. Example: A room needing 120 CFM with a 50-foot equivalent run at 0.10\" friction rate needs a 7\" round duct or 8x6\" rectangular duct. CONSEQUENCES OF SKIPPING: 1) Undersized ducts = high static pressure, noise, reduced airflow, hot/cold rooms. 2) Oversized ducts = wasted material cost and space. 3) Imbalanced system = some rooms get too much air, others get too little. 4) The #1 reason customers have comfort complaints after a new system install is improper duct design — the equipment is perfect but the delivery system is wrong. It's like buying a Ferrari and driving it on a dirt road."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A customer's flex duct in the attic has collapsed in multiple sections. What's the proper repair/replacement approach?",a:"Collapsed flex duct is one of the most common residential HVAC problems — and one of the biggest energy wasters. Assessment: 1) Inspect EVERY run in the attic, not just the visible ones. If one col..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Calculate the CFM requirement for a 2,000 sq ft home with a 3-ton AC system. Then size the return duct for this system.",a:"CFM Calculation: Standard rule: 400 CFM per ton of cooling capacity. 3-ton system = 3 × 400 = 1,200 CFM total airflow required. However, always verify with the equipment data — some high-efficiency... WC per 100 feet (standard residential): For 1,200 CFM in a single return trunk: 20\" round duct or 24\" × 12\" rectangular duct. For a split return (two returns in a 2-story home): each handles 600 CFM = 16\" round or 18\" × 10\" rectangular each. COMMON MISTAKES: 1) Single small return in the hallway — can't move 1,200 CFM through one 14\" × 6\" grille. This is the #1 cause of high return static and short cycling. 2) No return path from bedrooms with closed doors — air can't circulate. Solution: jump ducts or transfer grilles above each bedroom door. 3) Return located next to the supply register — short circuits the airflow. A properly sized return duct system is more important than the supply system for overall comfort and efficiency — yet it's the most neglected part of residential HVAC."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is the Manual J load calculation and why is it the foundation of every HVAC installation?",a:"Manual J is the ACCA-standard method for calculating the heating and cooling loads of a building — it determines HOW MUCH heating/cooling the home needs. It accounts for: 1) Building envelope: wall..."}
      ]},
    {id:28,name:"Colorado Plumbing Code Essentials",category:"Plumbing",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:true,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"What are the key Colorado-specific plumbing code requirements every JT expert must know?",a:"1) Water heater expansion tanks are REQUIRED on any new water heater install when a PRV or backflow preventer exists on the main (which is most homes in Greeley). 2) Water heater T&P discharge must... of the floor or to the exterior — cannot discharge into a wall cavity or attic. 3) Minimum water line burial depth is 42\" below grade (frost line for Northern Colorado). 4) Gas line pressure test: 3 PSI for 15 minutes minimum with air or nitrogen. 5) All new plumbing work requires a permit in Weld County — this includes water heater replacements. 6) Drain, Waste, and Vent (DWV) testing: water test or air test at 5 PSI for 15 minutes. 7) PEX is approved for residential water distribution in Colorado. 8) All accessible cleanouts must have minimum 18\" clearance. Know these cold — inspectors in Weld County are strict and callbacks for code violations cost us time and reputation."},
        {q:"A customer says 'My last plumber didn't pull a permit. Do you really need one?' What's the response?",a:"'I understand — and unfortunately that's common in our industry. Here's why we always pull permits: 1) It's the law. Any work involving new gas lines, water heaters, sewer lines, or major plumbing ..."},
        {q:"What are the venting requirements for a gas water heater and when must you upgrade the vent?",a:"Standard atmospheric (natural draft) gas water heater: Type B double-wall metal vent, minimum 1\" clearance to combustibles, must terminate above the roofline per manufacturer specs (usually 12\" minimum above roof penetration). When to upgrade: 1) Switching from a 40,000 BTU to a 50,000+ BTU unit — the existing vent may be undersized. Refer to the BTU-to-vent-size table. 2) Installing a power vent or direct vent unit — these use PVC/CPVC venting, not metal B-vent. Cannot connect to existing B-vent. 3) If the existing B-vent shows corrosion, separation, or improper pitch (must slope 1/4\" per foot upward). 4) If the furnace and water heater share a common vent (chimney) and you're replacing only the water heater with a different BTU rating — the common vent must be resized for the new combined BTU. 5) High-efficiency condensing water heaters require 2-pipe PVC venting (intake + exhaust). Always check vent sizing — an undersized vent causes backdrafting, which puts carbon monoxide into the home."},
        {q:"A Weld County inspector fails your water heater installation. What are the most common reasons and how do you avoid them?",a:"Top 5 failure reasons: 1) Missing expansion tank — required when a PRV or check valve exists on the main line. Inspectors check every time. 2) T&P discharge improper — too short, wrong material, ca... of the floor. 3) Gas flex connector too long — maximum length varies by jurisdiction, typically 72\" in Weld County. Must be accessible and not through walls or floors. 4) Missing drip leg/sediment trap on the gas line — a 3-6\" vertical pipe below the gas inlet to catch debris. Takes 2 minutes to install and inspectors always look for it. 5) Improper venting — wrong clearance to combustibles, improper slope, or incorrect vent sizing. Prevention: use our installation checklist on EVERY job. It matches the inspector's checklist point by point. Treat every install as if the inspector is coming tomorrow — because in Weld County, they usually do within 48 hours."},
        {q:"What drain line sizing and slope requirements apply to residential work in Colorado?",a:"Sizing by fixture: Lavatory: 1.25\" minimum. Kitchen sink: 1.5\" minimum (2\" preferred). Toilet: 3\" minimum (4\" for main building drain). Shower: 2\" minimum. Washing machine: 2\" minimum standpipe. Main building drain: 4\" minimum. Slope requirements: 1/4\" per foot for pipes 3\" and smaller. 1/8\" per foot for pipes 4\" and larger. Too much slope is as bad as too little — if the slope exceeds 1/2\" per foot, water outruns solids and you get buildup. This is a common problem in homes with basements where the main line drops steeply to the sewer connection. Always check slope with a level during rough-in and final. Inspectors measure it. A pipe that's 1/16\" per foot won't pass — it needs the full 1/4\" per foot on 3\" and under."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Explain the fixture unit system used in Colorado plumbing code for drain sizing. Size the building drain for a typical 3-bathroom home.",a:"Drainage Fixture Units (DFU) assign a numerical value to each fixture based on its flow rate. Standard values: Toilet = 4 DFU, Lavatory = 1 DFU, Bathtub/Shower = 2 DFU, Kitchen sink = 2 DFU, Dishwa... per foot slope): 3\" pipe = 42 DFU maximum → 30 DFU fits. However, 4\" pipe is standard for building drains because: 1) Allows for future additions. 2) Handles 216 DFU — significant capacity margin. 3) Required by many jurisdictions for the building sewer. 4) Matches the typical city sewer tap size. Important code note: no more than 2 toilets on a 3\" horizontal branch. The third toilet requires its own branch or an upsized main. This is a common plan review catch — inspectors count fixtures carefully."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What are the venting requirements in Colorado code? Explain wet venting, circuit venting, and air admittance valves.",a:"Every fixture trap requires a vent to prevent siphonage and maintain atmospheric pressure in the drain system. INDIVIDUAL VENT: Dedicated vent pipe from each fixture to the vent stack. Most reliabl... trap arm). Example: a bathroom group where the lavatory drain is the wet vent for the toilet. CIRCUIT VENTING: A single vent serves multiple fixtures connected to a horizontal branch. Maximum 8 fixtures on a circuit vent. The vent connects between the last two fixtures on the branch. COMMON in multi-bathroom residential construction. AIR ADMITTANCE VALVES (AAV/Studor vents): One-way mechanical vents that open under negative pressure (allowing air in) and close under positive pressure (preventing sewer gas escape). Colorado DOES allow AAVs under specific conditions: cannot be the only vent for a building (at least one full atmospheric vent must extend through the roof), must be accessible for service, and cannot be used where structural performance venting is required. AAVs are lifesavers for island sinks and remodel situations where running a vent to the roof is impractical."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: A new kitchen island requires a sink with no nearby wall for venting. What are the code-compliant options in Colorado?",a:"Island sink venting is one of the most complex residential plumbing challenges. Options: 1) AIR ADMITTANCE VALVE (AAV/Studor vent): Install under the counter in an accessible location. The AAV allo..."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: What is a cross-connection in plumbing and what backflow prevention devices does Colorado code require?",a:"A cross-connection is any point where the potable water supply could be contaminated by a non-potable source. Examples: 1) A garden hose submerged in a swimming pool or attached to a chemical spray... above the highest downstream point. Not suitable for continuous pressure. REDUCED PRESSURE ZONE (RPZ) ASSEMBLY: Required for HIGH-HAZARD connections — irrigation systems with chemical injection, commercial fire sprinkler connections to potable water, commercial boiler fills. Must be tested annually by a certified backflow tester. DOUBLE CHECK VALVE (DCV): Required for LOW-HAZARD connections — fire sprinkler systems, dedicated irrigation without chemicals. For residential: 1) Every hose bib should have a vacuum breaker. 2) Irrigation systems connected to city water require at minimum a DCV, and Greeley typically requires an RPZ. 3) Boiler fills require a backflow preventer on the feed line. Failure to install proper backflow prevention can contaminate the entire neighborhood's water supply — the liability is enormous."},
        {q:"ADVANCED: Walk through the permit and inspection process for a whole-home repipe in Weld County. What does the inspector look for?",a:"Permit process: 1) Submit application to Weld County Building Department — include scope of work, address, contractor license number, and estimated cost. 2) Fee is based on valuation — typically $7... horizontally and 48\" vertically. Copper every 6-10 feet. 3) Proper separation from other trades — water lines must be 6\" minimum from electrical, 1\" from gas. 4) Expansion and contraction provisions — PEX must not be rigidly secured (allow for thermal movement). 5) Water test: pressurize to 80 PSI for 15 minutes with no drop. OR air test at 50 PSI for 15 minutes. 6) No prohibited fittings (shark bites in concealed locations are debated — check with YOUR inspector). FINAL INSPECTION (after walls closed): 1) All fixtures connected and operational. 2) No cross-connections. 3) Proper shut-off valves at every fixture. 4) Water heater connections comply. 5) Hot on the left, cold on the right at every fixture. 6) Flow test at furthest fixture. Pro tip: build a relationship with your local inspector. Walk the rough-in WITH them. Ask questions. They respect contractors who care about code compliance and they'll give you the benefit of the doubt on edge cases."}
      ]},
    {id:29,name:"Master Plumber — Piping & System Design",category:"Plumbing",required:false,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:false},
      lessons:[
        {q:"MASTER: Size the water supply system for a 3-bathroom, 2,400 sq ft home. Calculate fixture units, pipe sizing from meter to furthest fixture, and minimum main size.",a:"Step 1 — Count Water Supply Fixture Units (WSFU): Master bath (toilet 2.2, lav 1.0, tub/shower 2.0) = 5.2. Bath 2 (toilet 2.2, lav 1.0, tub/shower 2.0) = 5.2. Half bath (toilet 2.2, lav 1.0) = 3.2.... copper minimum. Branch lines: 3/4\" to bathroom groups, 1/2\" to individual fixtures. Step 4 — Verify velocity: 15.6 GPM through 1\" copper = 6.5 ft/sec (under the 8 ft/sec max to prevent erosion and water hammer). With PEX manifold system, each fixture gets a dedicated 1/2\" home run from the manifold, with 3/4\" main feed to manifold. This eliminates most sizing calculations but the main feed sizing still applies."},
        {q:"MASTER: Explain the differences between Schedule 40, Schedule 80, and SDR pipe ratings. When does each apply in residential and light commercial?",a:"SCHEDULE rating = wall thickness based on a nominal pipe size. Higher schedule = thicker wall = higher pressure rating. SCHEDULE 40 PVC (DWV): Standard for residential drain, waste, and vent. Press... sizes). Color: white. This is your everyday DWV and cold water pressure pipe. SCHEDULE 80 PVC: Thicker wall, higher pressure rating (210-300 PSI depending on size). Color: gray. Required when: pipe is exposed and subject to impact damage, higher pressure applications, chemical drainage (laboratories), or where code requires extra protection. 25-30% more expensive. SDR (Standard Dimension Ratio) = outer diameter divided by wall thickness. SDR 35: Thin wall, sewer main from house to city connection (gravity flow, no pressure). Cheapest option for underground gravity drains. SDR 26: Medium wall, underground building sewer where extra strength is needed (under driveways, heavy traffic areas). SDR 21: Thick wall, pressure-rated water service pipe (SDR 21 PVC is rated for 200 PSI). Used for water mains from city to meter. SDR 11: Very thick wall, used for high-pressure applications and gas piping (HDPE/PE). Master knowledge: always check the specific pressure/temperature rating printed on the pipe — schedule number alone doesn't tell you the full story because different materials (PVC, CPVC, ABS) have different pressure ratings at the same schedule."},
        {q:"MASTER: A customer's house has galvanized supply lines and they're getting pinhole leaks. Explain the metallurgy of why galvanized pipe fails and why spot-repair is a bad long-term strategy.",a:"Galvanized steel pipe is carbon steel coated with a zinc layer (galvanization) to resist corrosion. Failure mechanism: 1) The zinc coating provides 'sacrificial protection' — zinc corrodes preferen... to sometimes 1/4\". Why spot-repair fails: If one area has depleted its zinc, the ENTIRE system is at the same age. Fixing one leak guarantees another leak within months at the next weakest point. It's like patching one hole in a 50-year-old garden hose. The only permanent solution is full repipe. Present it clearly: 'Patching this leak is $350, but your entire system is the same age. I can almost guarantee another leak within 6 months. A full PEX repipe eliminates this cycle permanently.'"},
        {q:"MASTER: What is water hammer, what causes it, and what are the three engineering solutions? Include the physics.",a:"Water hammer (hydraulic shock): A pressure surge caused by the sudden stoppage of water flow. Physics: Water is nearly incompressible. When a valve closes abruptly (solenoid valves, quick-close fau... copper pipe with water flowing at 8 ft/sec: the instantaneous pressure spike can reach 500+ PSI — enough to rupture fittings, damage valves, and crack pipe joints. SOLUTION 1: WATER HAMMER ARRESTOR — a sealed chamber with a piston or bladder that absorbs the shockwave. Install within 6 feet of the offending valve (usually washing machine, dishwasher, or quick-close faucets). Size by fixture unit count. SOLUTION 2: EXPANSION TANK — on closed systems (with check valve/PRV), absorbs both thermal expansion and minor hammer events. Not a substitute for arrestors but complementary. SOLUTION 3: PRESSURE REDUCING VALVE — if incoming pressure exceeds 80 PSI, water hammer is amplified. Reducing to 50-65 PSI significantly reduces hammer severity. Also: ensure pipe velocity stays below 8 ft/sec (proper pipe sizing). Higher velocity = worse hammer. Master insight: PEX systems experience less severe water hammer than copper because PEX is slightly flexible — it absorbs some of the shockwave energy through pipe wall deformation. This is another selling point for PEX repipes."},
        {q:"MASTER: A house has low hot water pressure at all fixtures but cold water pressure is normal. The water heater is 3 years old. Diagnose systematically.",a:"This is a classic master plumber diagnostic because the water heater is new — everyone assumes it's the heater, but it usually isn't. Systematic approach: 1) MEASURE PRESSURE: Connect a gauge to th..."},
        {q:"MASTER: Explain the purpose of a plumbing trap, the physics of trap seal loss, and all the ways a trap can lose its seal.",a:"PURPOSE: The water seal in a P-trap (typically 2-4 inches of water depth) creates a barrier between the living space and the sewer system. Without it, sewer gases (methane, hydrogen sulfide, bacter..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A two-story house with a basement has the main sewer line running through the basement at 4' above the floor. A customer wants a bathroom in the basement. Design the system.",a:"The challenge: the basement bathroom fixtures are BELOW the main sewer line, so gravity drainage is impossible. Solution: SEWAGE EJECTOR SYSTEM. Design: 1) EJECTOR PIT: Install a sealed fiberglass ... diameter, 24\" deep) below the basement floor. The pit must be sealed and vented to prevent sewer gas escape. 2) EJECTOR PUMP: Install a sewage ejector pump (NOT a sump pump — sewage ejectors handle solids up to 2\" diameter) inside the pit. Size for the fixtures: a toilet alone requires a 4/10 HP minimum. A full bathroom (toilet + shower + sink) requires minimum 1/2 HP with 2\" discharge. 3) DISCHARGE LINE: 2\" PVC from the pump discharge, rising to connect to the main sewer line above the flood rim level of the highest fixture (typically above the basement ceiling). Install a check valve AND a gate valve on the discharge line. The check valve prevents backflow; the gate valve allows service. 4) VENTING: The ejector pit must be independently vented through the roof — this cannot be wet-vented. The vent allows the pump to discharge properly and prevents sewer gas buildup in the sealed pit. 5) FIXTURES: Toilet, shower, and lavatory all drain by gravity into the ejector pit. The shower requires a recessed pan since the drain is below the slab. 6) ELECTRICAL: Dedicated circuit for the pump, with a high-water alarm. Code requirements: Weld County requires a permit for any below-grade bathroom. The ejector pump must be accessible through a sealed, removable cover. The pit must be gas-tight. Cost presentation: 'A basement bathroom with ejector system runs $12,000-18,000 depending on the layout. The ejector pump adds about $2,500-3,500 to what a standard bathroom would cost, but it gives you a fully functional bathroom below the main sewer line.'"},
        {q:"MASTER: What is the difference between a sanitary tee, a wye, a combo, and a long-sweep 90 in DWV systems? When is each required by code?",a:"SANITARY TEE: A tee fitting with a slight directional sweep in the branch. Used ONLY on VERTICAL-to-horizontal connections (a vertical drain transitioning to horizontal). NEVER use a sanitary tee o..."},
        {q:"MASTER: Calculate the minimum vent stack size for a 4-story residential building with the following DWV loads: 48 total Drainage Fixture Units (DFU) on the building drain.",a:"Vent sizing is determined by three factors: 1) Size of the soil/waste stack being vented. 2) Total DFU load on the stack. 3) Developed length of the vent (from connection to termination through roo... drain (per UPC Table 7-3, a 4\" drain handles up to 216 DFU on a building drain at 1/4\" per foot slope). The vent stack size is determined by UPC Table 7-5: For a 4\" soil stack with 48 DFU and a vent developed length of ~50 feet (4-story building): minimum vent size = 2\". However, in practice: 3\" vent stack is standard for a 4-story building because: 1) Future-proofing for additional fixtures. 2) Less susceptible to frost closure at the roof termination (critical in Colorado — a 2\" vent can ice over in winter, blocking the vent entirely). 3) Some jurisdictions require 3\" minimum for buildings over 2 stories. FROST CLOSURE: Colorado code and good practice requires increasing the vent pipe by one size where it passes through the roof. If the vent is 3\" through the building, it increases to 4\" at the roof penetration. This prevents ice from fully blocking the opening during prolonged freezing. Frost closure symptoms: gurgling drains, slow drainage, and sewer gas smells in winter that disappear in spring. Master plumber insight: if you're troubleshooting winter-only drain problems in a multi-story building, check the vent termination for ice first."},
        {q:"MASTER: A customer on a well system has cloudy water that clears after running for 30 seconds and a rotten egg smell on the hot side only. Full diagnosis.",a:"Two separate but related issues: CLOUDY WATER (clears after running): 1) AIR IN THE SYSTEM: Well pumps can introduce air when the water level drops near the pump intake. The cloudiness is dissolved..."},
        {q:"MASTER: Explain thermal expansion in a closed plumbing system and calculate the expansion volume when 50 gallons of water is heated from 40°F to 140°F.",a:"CLOSED SYSTEM: Any plumbing system with a check valve, PRV (pressure reducing valve), or backflow preventer that prevents water from expanding back into the city main. When water heats, it expands ..."}
      ]},
    {id:30,name:"Advanced HVAC — Load Calculations & System Design",category:"HVAC",required:false,techs:{1:false,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"MASTER: What is Manual J and why can't you just use 'rules of thumb' to size HVAC equipment? Give a specific example where rule-of-thumb fails.",a:"Manual J (ACCA — Air Conditioning Contractors of America) is the industry-standard method for calculating residential heating and cooling loads. It accounts for: building envelope (insulation, wind..."},
        {q:"MASTER: Explain the refrigeration cycle in a split AC system. Include the state changes, pressures, and temperatures at each point.",a:"Four components, continuous cycle: 1) COMPRESSOR (outdoor unit): Receives low-pressure, low-temperature VAPOR from the evaporator (typically 70 PSI, 45°F for R-410A). Compresses it to high-pressure..."},
        {q:"MASTER: You measure the following on a R-410A system: suction pressure 100 PSI, liquid pressure 420 PSI, outdoor temp 95°F, indoor return 75°F/63°F WB. Superheat is 5°F and subcooling is 18°F. Diagnose the system.",a:"Convert pressures to temperatures using P-T chart: Suction 100 PSI R-410A = 37°F evaporating temperature. Liquid 420 PSI R-410A = 112°F condensing temperature. SUPERHEAT = actual suction temp - eva..."},
        {q:"MASTER: Explain the difference between a single-stage, two-stage, and variable-speed/modulating furnace. Include electrical, gas valve, and blower differences.",a:"SINGLE-STAGE: Gas valve: ON or OFF. One firing rate (100% capacity). Blower: single-speed or multi-speed PSC motor (you set the speed on the board tap). Thermostat: simple 2-wire (R-W). Operation: ..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A heat pump system isn't keeping up with heating demand when the outdoor temp drops below 25°F. The backup electric heat strips are running constantly. Diagnose and present options.",a:"Heat pump heating capacity decreases as outdoor temperature drops — this is fundamental to air-source heat pump physics. At 47°F outdoor, a heat pump delivers 100% of rated heating capacity. At 17°..."},
        {q:"MASTER: What is static pressure in an HVAC system and how do you measure it? What do the readings tell you?",a:"Static pressure is the resistance to airflow in the duct system, measured in inches of water column (\" WC). It's the HVAC equivalent of blood pressure — tells you the health of the air distribution system. MEASUREMENT: Use a manometer or digital pressure gauge with static pressure tips. Drill 3/8\" test holes in the supply and return plenums (after the filter, before the coil on the return side; after the heat exchanger/coil on the supply side). Insert the static pressure probe into each hole. READINGS: Total External Static Pressure (TESP) = Supply static + Return static. Example: Supply reads +0.35\" WC, Return reads -0.25\" WC. TESP = 0.60\" WC. INTERPRETATION: Most residential equipment is rated for 0.50\" WC total external static. 0.30-0.50\" WC: Normal — good airflow, proper duct sizing. 0.50-0.70\" WC: Elevated — restricted airflow, system working harder than designed. Check filter, coil, ductwork. 0.70-1.00\" WC: Critical — significant restriction. Compressor/blower stress, efficiency loss of 20-30%, premature equipment failure. Identify and correct the restriction immediately. Over 1.00\" WC: Severe — system is being damaged. Common causes: dirty filter, dirty evaporator coil, undersized ductwork, too many turns/elbows, closed registers, undersized returns. HIGH RETURN STATIC (over 0.30\" WC): Return ductwork is undersized or the filter is too restrictive. Add return air paths or switch to a less restrictive filter. HIGH SUPPLY STATIC (over 0.40\" WC): Supply runs are too long, too small, or have too many restrictions. Master insight: 80% of comfort complaints can be diagnosed with a static pressure reading. It's the single most underutilized diagnostic tool in residential HVAC."},
        {q:"MASTER: Explain the differences between R-410A, R-454B, and R-32 refrigerants. Include GWP, safety classifications, and installation implications.",a:"R-410A: Currently the standard residential refrigerant. GWP (Global Warming Potential) = 2,088. Safety class: A1 (non-toxic, non-flammable). Operating pressures: ~400 PSI high side. Phase-out: new ..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A customer's 20 SEER system is producing electric bills identical to their neighbor's 14 SEER system in a similar home. How is this possible?",a:"SEER is a RATING, not a guarantee. It represents efficiency under laboratory conditions. Real-world efficiency depends on installation quality and maintenance. Root causes for a high-SEER system un..."},
        {q:"MASTER: Describe the complete commissioning procedure for a new residential HVAC system. What measurements must be documented?",a:"Commissioning is the process of verifying that a newly installed system performs to design specifications. It's the difference between 'installed' and 'installed correctly.' STEP 1 — VERIFY INSTALL... WC total external. Measure airflow at each register using a balancing hood. Each room should receive its design CFM from Manual D. STEP 3 — REFRIGERANT VERIFICATION: Measure superheat at the suction line (TXV: 10-15°F; piston: use manufacturer's target superheat chart). Measure subcooling at the liquid line (10-12°F). Compare to manufacturer's charging chart for the specific outdoor/indoor conditions. STEP 4 — TEMPERATURE VERIFICATION: Supply air temperature: cooling mode delta-T of 18-22°F across the evaporator. Heating mode: supply air 110-130°F (varies by furnace). Each room temperature within 2°F of thermostat setpoint after 30 minutes of operation. STEP 5 — COMBUSTION ANALYSIS (gas furnace): Measure CO in the supply plenum (must be <9 PPM). Measure flue gas temperature and CO2 to verify heat exchanger integrity. STEP 6 — ELECTRICAL: Verify compressor amperage vs. nameplate RLA (should be within 10%). Verify blower motor amperage. Record capacitor readings (within 10% of rating). STEP 7 — CONTROLS: Test all modes: heat, cool, auto, emergency heat. Test safety controls: high-limit, flame rollout, pressure switch. Program thermostat and verify scheduling. STEP 8 — DOCUMENTATION: Record ALL measurements on the commissioning form. Provide the customer with a copy. File a copy in the job record. This documentation proves the system was installed correctly and is your warranty protection. MASTER INSIGHT: systems that are commissioned properly have 33% fewer callbacks in the first year and last 3-5 years longer than systems that are 'turned on and walked away from.'"}
      ]},
    {id:31,name:"Advanced Refrigerant & EPA Compliance",category:"HVAC",required:true,techs:{1:false,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"MASTER: What are the EPA Section 608 technician certification types and what does each allow you to do?",a:"TYPE I: Service small appliances containing less than 5 lbs of refrigerant (window units, PTAC units, reach-in coolers, residential refrigerators). No recovery requirement if the charge is under sp... Hg (no evacuation required for recovery); under 200 lbs = 0\" Hg for systems manufactured before 11/15/93, 10\" Hg after. For JT Plumbing: every HVAC tech must have Universal certification. Period. We pay for the test and study materials."},
        {q:"MASTER: You're recovering R-22 from an old system being replaced. Walk through the exact procedure and EPA requirements.",a:"R-22 is an ODS (Ozone Depleting Substance) — extra regulations apply. PROCEDURE: 1) IDENTIFY REFRIGERANT: Verify the nameplate says R-22. If you suspect contamination (previous technician may have ..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A system needs refrigerant added. How do you determine the correct charge amount without a nameplate?",a:"If the nameplate is missing or illegible, you CANNOT just add refrigerant until 'it feels cold.' Systematic approach: 1) IDENTIFY THE SYSTEM: Get the model number from the outdoor unit data plate (... liquid line, 0.2 oz per foot for 1/4\" liquid line). 3) IF MODEL IS UNKNOWN: Charge by superheat/subcooling method. For TXV systems: target subcooling of 10-12°F. Add refrigerant slowly (2-4 oz at a time), let the system stabilize for 15 minutes, remeasure. For piston/orifice systems: target superheat using the manufacturer's chart (requires outdoor ambient temp and indoor wet bulb temp). 4) WEIGH YOUR CHARGE: Always use a calibrated scale. Record the exact amount added on the service ticket. 5) VERIFY OPERATION: After charging, verify: suction and liquid pressures, superheat, subcooling, supply/return air temperature split (18-22°F), and compressor amperage (within 10% of RLA). COMMON MISTAKE: Adding refrigerant until the suction pressure 'looks right' without checking superheat/subcooling. This leads to overcharging on cool days and undercharging on hot days. Pressures change with ambient temperature — superheat and subcooling are the true indicators of correct charge."},
        {q:"MASTER: Explain the difference between superheat and subcooling. Why do we measure both, and what does each tell us about system operation?",a:"SUPERHEAT: The temperature of the refrigerant vapor ABOVE its boiling point at the current pressure. Measured at the suction line (between evaporator and compressor). Calculation: Actual suction li..."},
        {q:"MASTER: You connect to a system and both high and low side pressures are equal and match ambient saturation temperature. What happened?",a:"EQUALIZED PRESSURES at ambient temperature means the compressor is NOT running and the system has been off long enough for pressures to equalize (usually 10-15 minutes). But if the system is SUPPOS..."},
        {q:"MASTER: What is a TXV and how does it work? Compare it to a fixed orifice/piston metering device.",a:"TXV (Thermostatic Expansion Valve): A precision metering device that automatically adjusts refrigerant flow to maintain a target superheat at the evaporator outlet. COMPONENTS: 1) Sensing bulb — cl..."},
        {q:"MASTER: An R-410A system has liquid pressure of 480 PSI on a 95°F day. Normal is about 400-420 PSI. What are the possible causes and what's your diagnostic path?",a:"480 PSI liquid pressure on a 95°F day = condensing temperature of approximately 125°F (R-410A P-T chart). Normal condensing temp should be outdoor ambient + 15-20°F = 110-115°F. So condensing is ru... of the coil). FIX: check fan amp draw, verify fan blade condition, clear obstructions. 3) OVERCHARGED: Too much refrigerant = excess liquid backs up in the condenser, reducing effective condenser surface area. CHECK: subcooling — if over 15°F with high head pressure, likely overcharged. FIX: recover excess refrigerant. 4) NON-CONDENSABLES (AIR) IN THE SYSTEM: Air in the system acts as a blanket on the condenser, raising pressure. Usually introduced through improper evacuation during installation or after a compressor replacement. CHECK: after shutting down, does the pressure settle to HIGHER than the ambient P-T reading? If system pressure at rest is higher than what the P-T chart says for ambient temp, non-condensables are present. FIX: recover all refrigerant, evacuate to 500 microns, recharge with virgin refrigerant. 5) LIQUID LINE RESTRICTION DOWNSTREAM: A restriction (kinked line, clogged filter-drier) between the condenser and metering device causes liquid to back up in the condenser. CHECK: temperature drop across the filter-drier — more than 3°F = restricted. FIX: replace the filter-drier."},
        {q:"MASTER: What is the proper evacuation procedure for a new R-410A system installation? Include micron targets, hold tests, and common evacuation failures.",a:"Evacuation removes moisture and non-condensable gases from the refrigerant system. Moisture + R-410A + POE oil forms acids that destroy the compressor. PROCEDURE: 1) CONNECT VACUUM PUMP: Use a pump... minimum) vacuum-rated hoses. Core removers on the service valves are critical — Schrader cores restrict flow and slow evacuation dramatically. 2) PULL VACUUM: Run the pump continuously. Monitor with a MICRON GAUGE (not a manifold gauge — manifold gauges can't read vacuum accurately enough). The system must reach 500 microns or below. 3) HOLD TEST: Once at 500 microns, close the valve between the pump and the system (isolate the pump). Wait 10 minutes. If the micron reading: STAYS below 500: system is tight and dry. Proceed to release refrigerant. RISES SLOWLY to 1,000-2,000 and stabilizes: residual moisture is boiling off. Reconnect pump and continue evacuating. Repeat hold test. RISES RAPIDLY above 2,000 and keeps climbing: there's a LEAK in the system. You must pressurize with nitrogen and leak-test BEFORE continuing evacuation. COMMON FAILURES: 1) Using the manifold gauge instead of a micron gauge — you can't see 500 microns on a compound gauge. 2) Leaving Schrader cores in during evacuation — adds 3-4x to evacuation time. 3) Using small hoses — 1/4\" hoses restrict vacuum flow. Use 3/8\" or core removers to bypass the valve. 4) Contaminated vacuum pump oil — change oil before every evacuation for best performance. 5) Rushing — a system that 'won't get below 1,000 microns' has moisture. Be patient. Deep vacuum boils water at room temperature. It takes time but it's the only way to properly dehydrate the system. NEVER release refrigerant into a system that hasn't passed a hold test at 500 microns."}
      ]},
    {id:32,name:"Thermostat, Controls & Electrical Diagnostics",category:"HVAC",required:true,techs:{1:true,2:false,3:true},
      lessons:[
        {q:"MASTER: Map out the complete 24V control circuit for a standard gas furnace with AC. Label every terminal and wire function.",a:"The 24V control circuit is the 'brain' of the HVAC system. TRANSFORMER: Steps down 120V (or 240V) to 24V AC. Two output wires: R (24V hot) and C (24V common/neutral). THERMOSTAT TERMINALS: R — 24V ..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A smart thermostat won't power up after installation. The old thermostat worked fine. Diagnose the issue.",a:"The #1 cause: missing C wire. Old mercury or basic digital thermostats were powered by 'stealing' current through the R-W or R-Y circuit (power stealing). Smart thermostats (Nest, Ecobee, Honeywell..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A furnace control board is flashing a fault code. How do control boards work and what are the diagnostic steps?",a:"Modern furnace control boards are microprocessor-based — they run the entire ignition sequence and monitor all safety circuits. IGNITION SEQUENCE (IFC — Integrated Furnace Control): 1) Thermostat c..."},
        {q:"MASTER: Explain how a flame sensor works at the electrical level. Why does it get dirty, and what's the exact cleaning procedure?",a:"OPERATING PRINCIPLE: The flame sensor uses FLAME RECTIFICATION — the ability of a flame to conduct DC current. The control board sends a small AC voltage (usually 120V AC through a high-impedance c..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A contactor on an outdoor AC unit is chattering (rapidly engaging and disengaging). What are the possible causes?",a:"Contactor chatter is the rapid make-and-break of the contactor coil, causing the contacts to bounce. It sounds like a rapid clicking or buzzing from the outdoor unit. CAUSES: 1) LOW CONTROL VOLTAGE..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A customer's furnace blower motor runs continuously even when the thermostat is off. Diagnose systematically.",a:"The blower relay is being energized or bypassed. SYSTEMATIC APPROACH: 1) CHECK THE THERMOSTAT: Is the FAN switch set to ON instead of AUTO? This is the most common cause — the customer accidentally..."},
        {q:"MASTER: You need to wire a heat pump thermostat with dual fuel (heat pump + gas furnace backup). Walk through the complete wiring.",a:"Dual fuel combines a heat pump for mild weather heating with a gas furnace for extreme cold. The thermostat must manage both systems and switch between them based on outdoor temperature (the 'balan..."},
        {q:"MASTER: A capacitor reads within spec on your meter but the compressor still won't start. What's happening?",a:"A capacitor can read correct MFD on a meter but still fail under load. This is because your meter tests the capacitor with a very small voltage (typically 1-5V), while the capacitor must perform un..."}
      ]}
  ];
